# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banff-national-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The **1964 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **IX Olympic Winter Games** (German: *IX.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*) and commonly known as **Innsbruck 1964** (Austro-Bavarian: *Innschbruck 1964*), were a winter multi-sport event which was celebrated in Innsbruck, Austria, from January 29 to February 9, 1964.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The city was already an Olympic candidate, unsuccessfully bidding to host the 1960 Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Innsbruck won the 1964 Games bid, defeating the cities of Calgary in Canada and Lahti in Finland.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The sports venues, many of which were built for the Games, were located within a radius of 20 km (12 mi) around Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Games included 1,091 athletes from 36 nations, which was a record for the Winter Games at the time.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Athletes participated in six sports and ten disciplines which bring together a total of thirty-four official events, seven more than the 1960 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The luge made its debut on the Olympic program.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Three Asian nations made their Winter Games debut: North Korea, India and Mongolia.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union broke the record for the most gold and overall medals at a single Winter Olympics, with eleven and twenty five respectively, and finished first in the medal table.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The USSR was followed by Austria, the host country, which won twelve medals, four of which were gold.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Soviet athletes Lidia Skoblikova won all four women's races of speed skating and Klavdiya Boyarskikh won all three events of cross-country skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Swedish cross-country skier Sixten Jernberg, a three-time medalist at these Games, became the first athlete to collect nine medals at the Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In alpine skiing, the French sisters Christine and Marielle Goitschel each obtained a gold and a silver medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Before the Games, the Austrian army was mobilized to deal with the lack of snow.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] They brought thousands of cubic meters of it from Brenner Pass, close to the Italian border.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic Winter Games was held for a second time at Innsbruck in 1976.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic Torch was carried by Joseph Rieder, a former alpine skier who had participated in the 1956 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Games were affected by the deaths of Australian alpine skier Ross Milne and British luge slider Kazimierz Kay-Skrzypeski, during training, and by the deaths, three years earlier, of the entire United States figure skating team and family members.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The city of Innsbruck submitted its first Olympic bid in the 1950s to host the 1960 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Austrians had a convincing bid and were viewed as the favorites to host the games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] However, in the second round of the vote the members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) selected the American city of Squaw Valley due to its ambitious designs.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] A month later, the Innsbruck authorities decided to enter a bid again for the 1964 Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] On 26 May 1959, during the 55th session of the (IOC) in Munich, West Germany, the Austrians were selected in a landslide for the Games with 49 votes in the first round, ahead of Calgary (Canada), which obtained 9 votes and Lahti (Finland), which did not receive a vote.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Despite the construction of the Berlin Wall by East Germany in 1961, which increased tensions between East and West and the fact that the East Germans wanted to have their own team, the IOC managed to maintain the United Team of Germany for the third consecutive Olympiad.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the 1960s, the IOC also discussed the Olympic participation of South Africa, a country immersed in the apartheid regime.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] During the Games in Innbruck, the IOC President Avery Brundage announced that the country would not be able to participate in the 1964 Summer Olympics because of its policy of racial segregation in sport.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] On the other hand, several African countries which had become independent joined the Olympic movement: the national Olympic committees of Algeria, of Congo, from Nigeria and Sierra Leone were recognized by the IOC during the session held during the Innsbruck Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The number of IOC member nations increased to 114.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In addition, the Innsbruck Games were used for the dissemination of political messages.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Five Iranian students were arrested after marching with banners hostile to the shah.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Twenty other Iranians, who demonstrated for the release of prisoners in their country, were also imprisoned.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Organizing Committee of the IX Winter Olympics in Innsbruck 1964 was formed on 2 June 1959.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Heinrich Drimmel, President of the Austrian Olympic Committee and Federal Minister of Education, was elected as its president and Friedl Wolfgang was elected as its secretary-general.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Innsbruck Games cost around one billion schillings, or 40 million US dollars distributed among the organizing committee, the Austrian state, the Land of Tyrol and the city of Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The organizers tried to reduce the expenses related to the provisional elements, and to invest more money for the facilities which would continue to be used after the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympiaeisstadion costs 75 million schillings, the renovation of the Bergisel Ski Jump 15 million and the Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck 10 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The development of ski slopes, cross-country skiing and biathlon required a total of 29 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic village, intended to become a leisure center, costs 174 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] A total of 225 million was invested to renovate and develop the road network in the region.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The 1964 edition was the third time that the Winter Games were broadcast on television and the second time that exclusive broadcasting rights were sold.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] This was a substantial increase: where they were US$50,000 in 1960, the broadcast rights yielded US$937,000 in 1964, which was approximately 24 million schillings.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The American channel ABC paid nearly 15.4 million schillings, or 64 per cent of the broadcast rights revenue.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Eurovision network spent around 7.6 million for 16 countries, the Soviet television 600,000 Rbls and the Intervision network US$550,000 for six countries in Western Europe.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The CTV Television Network paid CA$5,000 for the exclusive broadcast rights in Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Games were held over twelve days, from January 29 to February 9.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Thirty-four events were on the program, an increase from the twenty-seven at Squaw Valley four years earlier.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Three luge events (individual men and women, doubles men) were included in the Olympic program.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Bobsled, which was absent from the 1960 Games due to the cost of building the track, returned to the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Ski jumping was divided into two events (small and large hill) and the women's 5-kilometer was added in cross-country skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Ice stock sport (Eisstockschießen), a variant of curling popular in Alpine countries, was a demonstration sport as in Garmisch-Partenkirchen in 1936.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In total, 1,073,000 people attend the various events.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The disciplines which attracted the most spectators were alpine skiing and ice hockey.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] † The numeral indicates the number of event finals for each sport held that day.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the weeks leading up to the Games, temperatures often rose above zero degrees Celsius due to the foehn, a hot, dry wind.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] There was no major snowfall for seven weeks, and the rain melted snow and ice at sports venues.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] This was the first time in around a century that the snowfall had been so low in Tyrol.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Two weeks before the start of the Games, thousands of Austrian soldiers were mobilized to transport by truck 40,000m3 of snow from the Brenner Pass, close to the Italian border, and spread it by hand on the ski slopes.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] 20,000m3 of snow was built up and 20,000 blocks of ice were transported to the bobsleigh and toboggan run.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Opening Ceremony took place on January 29 at the Bergisel Ski Jump stadium in front of approximately 50,000 spectators.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Games were opened by the President of Austria Adolf Schärf.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The bobsledder Paul Aste took the Olympic oath.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Aste modified the oath slightly: instead of saying "for the glory of sport and the honor of our countries", he replaced the word "country" with "teams" to remove the nationalist elements of the oath.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic flame of the Winter Games has been lit in front of the Temple of Hera in Olympia, Greece.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the stadium, the alpine skier Josef Rieder lit the cauldron.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Tyrolean orchestras performed during the ceremony.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The biathlon made its second Olympic appearance.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] As in 1960, the only event contested was a 20-kilometer cross-country ski race with four shooting ranges of 100 to 250 meters.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Soviet athlete Vladimir Melanin, a heavy favorite, won the event.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] This was the first time he did not miss any of his twenty shots in a major competition.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] His compatriot Aleksandr Privalov, who also had a clean shoot, was second by more than three minutes and the Norwegian Olav Jordet, who missed a target, won the bronze medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Finn Veikko Hakulinen was the fastest, but missed six shots and finished 15th.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh was not on the program for the 1960 Winter Olympic Games, at Squaw Valley in the United States, because of the low number of crews and the cost of building the track.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In 1964, bobsleigh events made a comeback and were contested on the Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Neither of the two Olympic champion teams, Great Britain and Canada, had a track in their country at the time.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] During the first round of the two-man event, the bobsleigh of the British Robin Dixon and Tony Nash was damaged and the competition's favorite, the Italian Eugenio Monti, lent them an axle bolt.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] After two rounds, the British beat the two Italian teams.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] After the third set, the Italians Sergio Zardini and Romano Bonagura beat Dixon and Nash by just five hundredths of a second.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, Dixon and Nash become Olympic champions with 12 hundredths ahead of silver medalists Zardini and Bonagura and 73 over third, Eugenio Monti and Sergio Siorpaes.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] This is the only time in history that the British have been Olympic bobsleigh champions.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] After the Games, Monti received the first International Fair Play Committee Pierre de Coubertin World Trophy for his sportsmanship towards the British team.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Canadians surprised in the four-man bobsleigh event.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] As the country competed for the first time in the Olympic bobsleigh events, the pilot's team Vic Emery won the first round, breaking the track record, and increased his lead in the following three rounds.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Canada won gold by more than a second ahead of Erwin Thaler 's Austrian bobsleigh and Eugenio Monti' s Italian bobsleigh.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Nordic combined event took place in the village of Seefeld in Tirol.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] On the first day, the competitors did three jumps and the two best results are recorded.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The next day, they did a 15-kilometer cross-country ski race.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The final ranking was established with a new points system.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The reigning Olympic champion, the German Georg Thoma, was first ahead of the Norwegian Tormod Knutsen and the Soviet Nikolay Kiselyov after the jumps.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Knutsen needed to beat Thoma by at least twelve seconds in the cross-country ski race to pass him, which he did, winning by 1.33 and becoming Olympic champion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Thoma, who had wax problems and fell twice during the race, was third, just 0.16 points behind Kisseliov after a tenth-place finish in cross-country skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The matches of ice hockey were played in the Olympiaeisstadion and the Messehalle.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The sixteen participating teams first played a match to determine their group for the rest of the competition: group A (which allocates places 1 to 8) or group B (places 9 to 16).
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Then, each team faced the other seven of its group.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In Group A, the Soviet favorites won their seven matches and became Olympic champions.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The tournament was actually very close since in the last game, the Soviets were losing 2–1 against Canada after two periods to finally win 3–2; if Canada had won they would have taken the gold medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Behind the Soviet Union, three teams had five wins and two losses: Canada, Czechoslovakia and Sweden.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] These three teams were ranked by goal difference with Sweden receiving silver, Czechoslovakia bronze and Canada finishing fourth.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Canadians, who were not satisfied with the method used to decide between Sweden and Czechoslovakia, boycotted the medal ceremony.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Luge was a popular sport in the Alpine countries, the first competition of which dates back to 1831.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The first international event was organized in 1928.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The IOC decided in 1954 to include luge in the program of the 1964 Games to replace the skeleton, because there was only one track adapted to this sport: the Cresta Run of Saint-Moritz in Switzerland.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Three events were contested at the Games: individual for men and women and two for men.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Some commentators believed that luge was too dangerous a sport to enter the Olympic program.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The death of Poland-born British luger Kazimierz Kay-Skrzypeski during a test run two weeks before the start of the Games helped reinforce this position.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The luge events were dominated by the Germans, who took five out of six medals individually.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] During the men's individual event, a German trio dominated the competition: the 1962 world champion Thomas Köhler as well as Klaus Bonsack and Hans Plenk were the top three in each of the first three rounds, won respectively by Köhler, Bonsack and again Köhler.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, Köhler became an Olympic champion, 27 hundredths of a second ahead of Bonsack and 3.38 seconds ahead of Plenk.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The German Ilse Geisler, world champion in 1962 and 1963, was the favorite in the women's event.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] However, it was her compatriot Ortrun Enderlein who won the first three races.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Geiser took a lot of risks in the last heat and made a big mistake, letting Enderlein win again.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Enderlein became Olympic champion, almost three seconds ahead of Geisler.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Austrian Helene Thurner won the bronze medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The doubles event, which takes place over two rounds, was dominated by the Austrians.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Indeed, Josef Feistmantl and Manfred Stengl won the first round ahead of Reinhold Senn and Helmut Thaler.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The latter won the second round without worrying Feistmantl and Stengl, crowned Olympic champions.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Italians Walter Ausserdorfer and Sigisfredo Mair are bronze medalists.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The figure skating events were held at the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Individually, men and women performed a free skate and compulsory figures while, for the last time in an international competition, the couples only presented one program.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Computers are used for refereeing, which is new to the Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The data processing system provided by the company IBM allows scores to be announced instantly.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In addition to figure skating, information is sent to a data center at University of Innsbruck from eleven other facilities.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the men's event, the German Manfred Schnelldorfer became Olympic champion by winning each round.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Frenchman Alain Calmat, slightly favored before the Olympics, finished in second place.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The American Scott Allen won the bronze medal, just two days before his fifteenth birthday.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] He thus became the youngest medalist in the history of the Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The big favorite in the women's event, the Dutch Sjoukje Dijkstra, easily became Olympic champion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] She is in fact placed in the first row by the nine judges.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In front of the Dutch royal family, she won the first Dutch gold medal at the Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Austrian Regine Heitzer was the silver medalist with a small lead over the Canadian Petra Burka.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviets Ludmila Belousova and Oleg Protopopov, a married couple, narrowly won the pair event ahead of the German Marika Kilius and Hans-Jürgen Bäumler.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The bronze medals went to Canadians Debbi Wilkes and Guy Revell.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In 1966, Kilius and Bäumler had to return their medals because of a professional contract signed before the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Canadians received the silver medal and the Americans Vivian and Ronald Joseph, initially fourth, received the bronze medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In 1987, however, the IOC decided to restore the medals of the German couple.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The results then plunged into confusion since the different rankings did not indicate the same information.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In 2013, the IOC clarified that the Soviets had the gold medal, the Canadians and the Germans shared the silver medal and the Americans the bronze medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] These were the official results since 1987.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The speed skating events took place on an outdoor track set up around the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] While the Soviets dominated the women's events, the men's podiums are more international.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The American Terry McDermott, who was not one of the favorites, won the men's 500 meters setting a new Olympic record.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Taking part in his first international competition, he borrowed skates from his trainer Leo Freisinger.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Three athletes, including the favorite of the event Yevgeny Grishin, shared second place.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviet Ants Antson won the gold medal in the 1,500 meters, ahead of the Dutch Kees Verkerk and the Norwegian Villy Haugen, after a very close race.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Norwegians score a hat-trick in the 5,000 meters.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Knut Johannesen is a gold medalist beating the Olympic record just two-tenths ahead of Per Ivar Moe.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, the Swede Jonny Nilsson won the 10,000 meters ahead of the Norwegians Fred Anton Maier and Knut Johannesen.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] This race was controversial because Nilsson was one of the few to skate before the wind picked up, and enjoyed better ice than most of the other competitors.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviet Lidia Skoblikova won all four races at the 1963 world championships.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] A big favorite, she reproduced the same performance at the 1964 Olympic Games, breaking the Olympic record each time.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] She thus becomes the first athlete to win four gold medals in one edition of the Winter Games and the first, after her two titles in 1960, to accumulate six gold medals in several editions.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Skoblikova first won the 500 meters ahead of her compatriots Irina Yegorova and Tatyana Sidorova.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] On 1,000 meters, she was ahead of Irina Iegorova and the Finn Kaija Mustonen.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] She dominated the 1,500 meters, with a time almost three seconds ahead of Mustonen.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, Skoblikova took the 5,000 meters with almost four seconds.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The North Korean Han Pil-hwa, unknown before the Games, created a surprise: tied with Skoblikova halfway through the course, she was ended up tied for second with the Soviet Valentina Stenina.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] North Korea participated in the Games for the first time; that was the country's first Olympic medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Upon her return home, Skoblikova was made a member of the Communist Party and became the first woman to win the title of Soviet Sportsman of the Year.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time in 1964, two ski jumping events were contested at the Olympic Games: small hill, contested at Toni-Seelos-Olympiaschanze and big hill, which takes place at Bergisel Ski Jump.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] They have a construction point of 70 and 90 meters respectively.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Athletes jump three times and their two best results count in each event.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Czechoslovak Josef Matouš surprised many by winning the first round of the normal hill while the Finn Veikko Kankkonen, who was among the favorites, was only twenty-ninth.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Kankkonen had the best jump of the competition in the second set, at 80 meters, and the Norwegian Toralf Engan took the lead.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] After the third round, Kankkonen who again produced a good jump, became Olympic champion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Toralf Engan was second while young Norwegian Torgeir Brandtzæg took third place.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the first round of the big hill, Veikko Kankkonen took the lead in front of Toralf Engan with a jump of 95.5 meters.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Engan took the first place after the second jump, while Kankkonen and Brandtzæg followed closely behind.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Brandtzæg finished with a good jump unlike his two rivals.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The medalists are the same as for the normal hill, but this time Engan is Olympic champion ahead of Kankkonen.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Most alpine skiing events were held at Axamer Lizum, with the men's downhill being held at the Patscherkofel (above Igls).
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Three events were on the program for men and women: downhill, giant slalom and slalom.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time at the Olympics, athletes were timed to the hundredth of a second.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The competition was held in mourning for the death of Australian Ross Milne, who crashed into a tree during downhill training.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Egon Zimmermann of Austria won the men's downhill, 74 hundredths of a second ahead of France's Léo Lacroix and 1.32 seconds over Wolfgang Bartels of Germany.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the last time at the Olympics, the men's giant slalom was held in a single round.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The French François Bonlieu won the race ahead of the Austrian favorites: Karl Schranz was second, and Josef Stiegler was third.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time, the Olympic slalom had a two-round qualifying phase.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The 25 best take part in the two final rounds which determine the ranking of the event.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Austrian officials tried to replace Josef Stiegler with Egon Zimmermann, but Stiegler competed in the slalom under public pressure.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Americans Billy Kidd and Jimmy Heuga, second and third respectively, won their country's first Olympic medals in alpine skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the women's downhill, the Austrians achieved the second treble in the history of the Winter Games in alpine skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The favorite Christl Haas was Olympic champion, more than a second ahead of Edith Zimmermann and Traudl Hecher.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The technical events were dominated by two French women, the Goitschel sisters.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Marielle Goitschel, aged 18, won the first round of the slalom ahead of her sister Christine, one year her senior.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Christine was the fastest, however, in the second run.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] She won gold, ahead of Marielle, while the bronze medal was awarded to the American Jean Saubert.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Two days later, Christine Goitschel took the lead in the giant slalom.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] His time was then equaled by Jean Saubert.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Marielle Goitschel, the fourteenth skier to set off, was almost a second ahead of them however.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The eldest Goitschel finished first this time, while her sister shared second place with Saubert.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The cross-country skiing events took place near the village of Seefeld in Tirol.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The men competed as usual in individual over 15, 30 and 50 kilometer as well as in the 4 × 10 kilometer relay.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] On the other hand, women competed for the first time at the Olympic Games the 5 kilometer, introduced at the world championships in 1962, in addition to the 10 kilometer and the relay 3 × 5 kilometer.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Men's events started with the 30 kilometers.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Finn Eero Mäntyranta won the race ahead of the Norwegian Harald Grønningen and the Soviet Igor Voronchikhin.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Swede Sixten Jernberg, the favorite after his six Olympic medals obtained in 1956 and 1960, finished fifth.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Eight of the top nine athletes were Scandinavian.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the 15 kilometer skied three days later, Eero Mäntyranta was once again crowned Olympic champion ahead of Harald Grønningen.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Sixten Jernberg wins bronze, his seventh Olympic medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Racing the day before his 35th birthday, Jernberg took the lead at the end of the 50 kilometer.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] He won gold, his eighth Olympic medal, finishing more than a minute ahead of his compatriot Assar Rönnlund.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The end of the relay 4 × 10 kilometer was a duel between the Finnish Eero Mäntyranta and the Swede Assar Rönnlund, who overtook the Soviet Pavel Kolchin one kilometer from the finish.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Sweden eventually won the event, eight seconds ahead of Finland and twelve over the Soviet Union.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Jernberg ended his Olympic career with nine medals including four gold, which was a new record.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Soviet skiers dominated the women's events as they won six of the seven possible medals.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the 10 kilometer they achieved the treble as in 1960: Klavdiya Boyarskikh ahead Yevdokiya Mekshilo and Maria Gusakova.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time among women, non-European cross-country skiers took part in the Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The two North Koreans and the two Mongols, however, finished in the last four places.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Boyarskikh also won the very close Olympic 5 km, while Finland's Mirja Lehtonen surprised by taking second place.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, the Soviets won the relay 3 × 5 kilometer for the first time.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] They were well ahead of the Swedes by two minutes and the Finns by three.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Klavdiya Boyarskikh wins his third gold medal at these Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time on games history, the Closing Ceremony was not held at the Olympic Stadium and in an indoor place, took place on February 9 at the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The flags of Greece, the founding nation of the Olympic Games, Austria, the host country, and France, the host country of the next Games, were raised to the sound of the national anthems.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The President of the IOC Avery Brundage officially declared the Games closed before the extinction of the Olympic flame.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Fourteen of the thirty-six nations which participated in these Games won at least one medal, as detailed in the table below.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Already first in 1956 and 1960, the Soviet Union came far ahead of this table with twenty-five medals: eleven gold, eight silver and six bronze, a new record for both gold and total medals won at a single Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The host country, ninth four years earlier, was second with twelve medals, including seven in alpine skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Norway, fourth in 1964, came third with fifteen medals.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviets also dominated the ranking of the most medal-winning athletes as the speed skater Lidia Skoblikova and cross-country skier Klavdiya Boyarskikh came first and second.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Several sports venues were built especially for the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] New slopes for alpine skiing were developed near the village of Axamer Lizum, about twenty kilometers from Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] There is a bobsleigh and luge track in Igls, seven kilometers south of Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The runway, 1506 meters long, had 14 curves and a drop of 138 meters.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time at the Games, the bobsleigh track used artificial ice.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympiaeisstadion, an eleven thousand-seat ice rink completed in 1963 and located in the center of Innsbruck, hosted the competitions of figure skating and most games of ice hockey.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The other hockey matches were played at the Messehalle.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The speed skating ring, made of artificial ice, was installed outside the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The ski jumping events were held on the Toni-Seelos-Olympiaschanze (normal hill) at Seefeld in Tirol and the Bergisel Ski Jump (big jump) in Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Bergisel ski jump, built in wood in 1920, was replaced by a concrete ski jump.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The cross-country skiing and biathlon tracks were located in Seefeld, like the small hill.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony was celebrated at the foot of the Bergisel ski jump while the closing ceremony took place at the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] An Olympic Village consisting of eight eleven-storey buildings was built outside the city.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] A total of 36 nations sent athletes to Innsbruck, six more than in Squaw Valley in 1960.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The total number of athletes was 1,091, up from 665 four years earlier.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Mongolia, India and North Korea participated in the Winter Games for the first time.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Belgium, Greece, Iran, Romania and Yugoslavia returned to this competition after missing it in 1960.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] On the other hand, South Africa and New Zealand, which took part in Squaw Valley, did not compete in Innsbruck.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] Athletes from West Germany (FRG) and East Germany (GDR) competed together as Unified Team Germany from 1956 to 1964.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The number indicated in brackets is the number of athletes entered in the official events for each country.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] There were also several injuries which occurred prior to the event.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] In the 1970s, the American city of Denver, chosen to host the 1976 Winter Olympics, rejected the bid after a statewide referendum.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] About ten cities applied to take over the Games and Innsbruck was selected.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The main reasons for this choice were the venues built for the 1964 Games, which kept costs down, and their good organization during the 1964 Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic venues subsequently hosted various sports competitions such as the Four Hills Tournament, Bobsleigh and Luge World Cup events, the Winter Universiade and the Ice Hockey World Championship in 2005 and the first Winter Youth Olympic Games in 2012.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The **1968 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **X Olympic Winter Games** (French: *Les Xes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*), were a winter multi-sport event held from 6 to 18 February 1968 in Grenoble, France.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The 1968 Winter Games marked the first time the IOC permitted East and West Germany to enter separately, and the first time the IOC ordered drug and gender testing of competitors.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Norway won the most gold and overall medals, the first time since the 1952 Winter Olympics that the Soviet Union did not top the medal table by both parameters.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 24 November 1960, François Raoul, the prefect of the Isère Département, and Raoul Arduin, the president of the Dauphiné Ski Federation, officially presented the idea of hosting the 1968 Winter Olympic Games in Grenoble.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After the city council agreed in principle, different government agencies offered their support, and the villages around Grenoble also reacted positively, an application committee was formed and led by Albert Michallon, the former mayor of Grenoble on 30 December 1960.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The application was officially given to the IOC during a meeting between IOC executives and representatives of international sport agencies in Lausanne in February 1963.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In the application, the decision was not solely based on sport, because there had only been two important sport events in the Isère Département: the Bobsleigh World Championships of 1951 in L'Alpe d'Huez and the Luge World Championships of 1959 in Villard-de-Lans.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Between 1946 and 1962, the number of inhabitants in Grenoble increased from 102,000 to 159,000, and the total inhabitants in the Département Isère increased from 139,000 to 250,000.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The development of the infrastructure could not keep up with this rapid increase, and was, for the most part, at the same level as before World War II.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The people who were responsible never made a secret out of it that it was mainly for them about using the Olympic Games to receive larger grants to quickly develop dated infrastructure and support the local economy.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The 61st IOC session, where the awarding of the Olympic Games would have been voted for, would have taken place in Nairobi, Kenya.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This session was moved to Baden-Baden, West Germany, because Kenya refused entry to IOC members from Portugal and apartheid South Africa for political reasons.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Due to a lack of time, only the 1968 Summer Olympics host city could be voted for.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The vote finally took place in Innsbruck on 28 January 1964, a day before the start of the 1964 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] 51 members who were eligible to vote were in attendance and Grenoble were awarded the games after the third round of voting and were competing against Calgary, who were awarded the Games 20 years later.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After Grenoble was voted as the host city, the French National Olympic Sports Committee decided the foundation of the organisation committee.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The Comité d'Organisation des dixièmes Jeux Olympiques (COJO), the committee for the organisation of the 10th Olympic Winter Games, started to plan the games for the first time on 1 August 1964.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Albert Michallon, alongside being the former mayor of Grenoble, was also president of COJO.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The upper panel was made up of the general assembly with its 340 members and the supervisory board conduct business with 39 members, 19 of which were appointed and the other 20 were voted for.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The general secretary consisted of five main departments and 17 subordinate departments.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The number of employees grew to 1920 in February 1968.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The French government played a major role in the preparations for the Games, as president Charles de Gaulle saw an opportunity to present Grenoble as a symbol for a modern France.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] François Missoffe, Minister for Youth and Sport, formed an interministerial committee for the coordination of the work commissioned by prime minister Georges Pompidou.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Over 7000 soldiers of the French armed forces and also employees of the ministries for Youth and Sport, Finance, Social Building, Education, Post, Culture and Transport were employed.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The sum of the investments contributed to CNF$1.1 billion Francs (roughly 775 million pounds).
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The government contributed 47.08%, the Isere Department 3.65%, the city of Grenoble 20.07% and the surrounding communities 1.37%.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Different institutions, such as the national train company SNCF; the television broadcaster ORTF; the government housing association and the regional association of hospitals provided the rest of the money.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] They built a new airport, two motorway sections of 7.5 miles and 15 miles, a switchboard, a new town hall, a new police station, a fire station, a hospital with 560 beds, a congress and exhibition centre and a culture palace.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] They upgraded the access road to the outer sport arenas, an orbital road round Grenoble as well as relocating the rail tracks and removing the level crossings and building a completely new main train station.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] To test the new sport complex and to improve organisational processes, they organized "International Sports Weeks".
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Speed skating competitions and ski races took place from 20 January to 19 February 1967; an ice hockey tournament from 12 to 15 October; and a figure-skating competition from 23 to 25 November.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 16 December 1967, the Olympic torch was lit in Olympia, Greece.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The ceremony would have taken place on 13 December, but was postponed due to the attempted coup d'état of King Constantine II, who had been forced from his throne eight months before, against the dictatorial military regime of Georgios Papadopoulos.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The torch relay in France went over a distance of 7,222 kilometers through 41 districts and 170 towns to the Isère district.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] 5,000 torchbearers, who transported the torch on foot, by bike, by boat, by skis or by motorbike, took part in the relay.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The first part of the relay was made at the old port of Marseille was done by a diver who, while swimming, held the torch just over the surface of the water.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The torchbearers were accompanied by around 80,000 athletes and watched by an audience of about two million people.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The last stop on the day before the opening ceremony was Saint-Pierre-de-Chartreuse.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] From there, the torch was carried to Grenoble.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The 33 torches that were used in the relay were produced by the Société technique d'équipement, a subsidiary of the Compagnie de Saint-Gobain.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] They were 70 cm tall, weighed 1750 g, were made of copper and had a propane gas tank.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The reserve flames (a cautionary measure in case the torch went out) burned in twenty carbide lamps, the same as the Olympic fire when it was transported from Athens to Paris in a plane.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The logo for the 1968 Winter Olympic Games portrays a floating snow crystal surrounded by three stylised roses on top of the single-coloured (in white) Olympic rings.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The roses can be found in the same pattern (two on the top and one below) as Grenoble's emblem.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the first time, there was an Olympic mascot, although it was unofficial.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The mascot was named Schuss, a stylised skier wearing a blue skiing costume and a large red ball as a head.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The mascot designed by Aline Lafargue was hardly recognised publicly.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It had unofficial character, was marked with great restraint and appeared solely on pins and several toys.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Jack Lesage, a videomaker who specialised in mountain and winter sport recordings, filmed two Olympic advertisements of 15–18 minutes in length before the Olympic Games took place and was contracted by the Organisation Committee.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] "Trois roses, cinq anneaux" ("Three roses, five rings") emerged in 1966, and showed Grenoble, as well as the surrounding venues, in the early stage of preparation.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In 1967, "Vaincre à Grenoble" ("Victory in Grenoble") emerged, and documented the progress of the workers, complemented with images of the sport competitions.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Both films appeared in three different versions with French, English and German commentary.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In France, the films were shown in cimemas before particular feature films, abroad for receptions and presentations.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The French post office issued six Olympic-themed postage stamps.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 22 April 1967, a label next appeared worth 0.60 francs with the official logo as its motif.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 27 January 1968, ten days before the opening ceremony, a series of five semi-postal stamps followed.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The proceeds from the supplement stamps were split between the French Red Cross and the Organisation Committee.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] There were five other venues surrounding Grenoble used as sporting venues for the Winter Olympic Games in 1968.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the first time in history, the venues were divided into four clusters.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Grenoble set a new trend by having venues in different parts of the surrounding areas.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Compared to the investments for the infrastructure, the investments for building sports arenas was very small.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This investment only contributed nine percent.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Almost half of this investment, 46 million Francs, was used to build the new ice rink *Stade de glace* (now *Palais des Sports*), the venue where the main ice hockey matches, the figure skating competition and the closing ceremony were held.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The arena has 12,000 seats and is situated in *Parc Paul Mistral*, Grenoble's main public park located in the center of the city.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The architects were Robert Demartini and Pierre Junillon.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Construction began in mid-November 1965 and finished in October 1967.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The roof was made of two cylindrical which crossed over each other, four columns which could support 10,000 tonnes.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Today, the arena is used for concerts, fairs and various other sporting events (among others, six-day races since 1971).
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Less than 100m away from the *Stade de glace*, and also in Parc Paul Mistral, the 400m track for the speed skating events was installed between February and November 1966.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The venue *Patinoire de vitesse*, which does not have a roof and has a practice ice-rink in the middle of it, had a capacity of 2,500.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The cooling system was removed after a few years and today the concrete track is used by roller skaters.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The existing was the city's ice-rink *Patinoire Municipale*, which opened in September 1963, next to the speed skating track, where the 1964 European Figure Skating Championships took place.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The arena, which has 2,000 seats and 700 can stand, was the venue for Group B's ice hockey matches.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The venue for the alpine skiing was Chamrousse, a town 30 kilometres east of Grenoble.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The finish line for five out of the six races was in the region of *Recoin de Chamrousse*, the other was the men's downhill event was in Casserousse.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In the construction of the new ski slopes, around 300,000m3 of rocks had to be blown up or dug away; particularly large movements of the earth and changes to the terrain were necessary in the upper part of the men's downhill section and in the slalom section.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In addition, six new chairlifts were installed.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In the preparation of the slopes, over 10,000 people were needed, this consisted mainly of soldiers.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In Autrans, 36 kilometres west of Grenoble in Vercors Massif, the cross-country skiing and biathlon events took place there.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Provisional stands at the finish line were available for spectators, which were to the north and southwest of the village.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Also in Autrans, the ski jumping in the normal hill took place.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The ski jumping hill of Le Claret is still in use today.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It originally had a hill size of 70m, but later was made bigger and now measures 90m high.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The 90m hill could have been built without any problems in Autrans, but the organisers decided instead to use Saint-Nizier-du-Moucherotte, 17 kilometres away from Grenoble, as well as Vercors-Massif.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The relatively small distance to the city and the better accessibility guaranteed a larger audience.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The construction period lasted from July 1966 to January 1967.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After the games, the Dauphine hill was rarely used and closed down and fell into ruin beginning in 1990.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] A third Olympic venue in the Vercors-Massif was Villard-de-Lans, 34 kilometres from Grenoble, where the luge competition took place.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The track is exactly 1,000m long, has 14 curves and has a drop of 110m.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After it temporarily closed down in 1994 it was remodelled.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Today, it now has an artificial surface which makes it possible to use all-year-round.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The third Olympic venue in Vercors Massif was 34 km away from Grenoble in the commune of Villard-de-Lans, where the luge competition took place.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The track for the luge was exactly 1 km long, had 14 corners and had a drop of 110m.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After the track was temporarily closed in 1994, it was rebuilt at today's location.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It has an artificial surface, which makes using the track all year round possible.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The furthest distance, which is also the highest, is L'Alpe d'Huez, 65 kilometres southeast of Grenoble.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh took place at Col de Poutran at a height of around 2,000m.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It was 1,500m long, had 13 corners and had a drop of 140m.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It was principally a natural course, but three of the corners were exposed to direct sunlight, and was kept artificially frozen by ammonia and liquid nitrogen.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In L'Alpe d'Huez, a replacement course was made available for the alpine skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The Olympic village was located in the southern part of the city on the border with the suburbs of Échirolles and Eybens.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The chosen place was the site of the former Grenoble-Mermoz Airport, a large housing estate with 6,500 rooms was built in two years.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After the games some areas was turned a primary school, secondary school, nursery, youth center, shopping center, and a library.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The public places are still in use today.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The male athletes were housed in a tower block and in eleven apartment blocks.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The female athletes lived in a building with 263 individual rooms, which later went on to serve as a home for workers.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Other buildings on the estate housed around 12,000 trainers, officials, timekeepers, volunteers, police and drivers.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The catering took place in a future school kitchen.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Two more secondary Olympic villages were available to the Nordic and Alpine skiers as well as their physios.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Holiday homes were also newly built and were located in Autrans and Chamrousse.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] A year before the Olympics, there was great adversity at the pre-Olympic competitions.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The accommodation did not meet the necessary standards, so much so the Austrian team left the village and housed in a local hotel.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This led the hosts to have a rethink and make improvements.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] There were 35 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In Grenoble, there were 1158 athletes and 37 teams, a new record in terms of the number of participants.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This was Morocco's first appearance at the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Similar to the 1952 Summer Olympics with Saarland, who had sent its own team but had not been integrated as a part of West Germany, there were two teams participating from Germany.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the first time, the German Democratic Republic (East Germany) was present with its own team.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It was provisionally accepted into the IOC, as long as it formed a complete German team consisting of athletes from both the West and East.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This had to be done under the leadership of the National Olympic Committee for Germany, a board recognised by the IOC.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Following on from this, the National Olympic Committee of East Germany tried to achieve complete recognition.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This did not work out because of resistance from Karl Ritter von Halt, the president of the National Olympic Committee for Germany, who was close friends with then-IOC president Avery Brundage.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After Halt died in 1961, the same year the Berlin Wall was built by East Germany to prevent the defections of its citizens to the West, the close contact with the IOC leadership was lost under his successor Willi Daume.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The reality of the split made the qualification almost impossible.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 8 October 1965, the IOC decided to accept East Germany as a full member.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Both national olympic committees agreed on using the same flag and anthem.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The black-red-gold flag with the white Olympic rings in the middle of it has been used at all Olympic Games since 1960, as well as the replacement anthem "Ode an die Freude" (Ode to Joy) from Beethoven's 9th symphony, which was used previously.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Both countries presented themselves as completely independent from 1972, using their respective national flags and anthems.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 21 January 1968, 21-year-old Ralph Pöhland, one of the most famous East German winter olympians, fled to West Germany after the pre-Olympic tournament at Les Bioux, Switzerland.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] His assistant in helping to flee was Georg Thoma, a West German ski jumper.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This incident led to relationships between the two German teams turning sour, which never used to be the case.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1968 Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the 1968 Winter Games, 228 gold, silver and bronze medals were manufactured in total, designed by Roger Excoffon and coined by French minting company Monnaie de Paris.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the first time in Olympic history, the medals, given out for the winners in every sport, had their own design.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The logo of the games was depicted on the front of the medal, and on the back was a pictogram etched into the surface that depicted the sport that the medal winner competed in.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The medals had a diameter of 50 mm (2 in) and were 3 mm (0 in) thick.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The gold and silver medals consisted of silver with a composition of 925/1000, but the gold medals were coated in an additional six grams of gold.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The medals hang of ribbons in the Olympic colours, which happened to also be a first, as they had used chains before 1968.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In addition, the athletes received a box made of black leather, lined with either white, blue or red silk.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The commemoration medal was designed by Josette Hébert-Coeffin.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The front side of the medal depicted the decorated head of a Greek athlete with snowflakes and ice crystals in the background.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The other side depicted the silhouette of Grenoble in front of the mountain range Belladonne.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] There were three different types of medals.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] 20 were made of silver, 210 of silver-coated bronze and 15,000 of bronze.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Excoffon also designed the Olympic diplomas, which were given to the six best athletes in each discipline.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] They were made of cream coloured parchment paper.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Around the logo contained the words "Xes Jeux Olympiques d'Hiver Grenoble 1968", as well as the Olympic motto "Citius, altius, fortius".
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In the middle of the paper, the word "Diplome" was written in gold writing.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] However, similar diplome were handed out to officials, participants, journalists and volunteers on ordinary white paper and without the gold writing as a souvenir.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The medal ceremonies took place in the evening of the finals event in the Stade de Glace.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Compared to the 1964 Winter Olympics in Innsbruck, the number of disciplines increased to 35, and the men's biathlon relay was also added.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 4 February, two days before the official opening ceremony, the first ice hockey preliminary matches took place.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] This games had a function to lead the vacant spots for 4 teams, the three winners are placed into Group A alongside the five teams already assigned to the group.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The losing team was placed into Group B.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For first time, a temporary stadium was built to host the ceremonies, supported by scaffolding and able to hold 60,000 spectators.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was situated in the immediate vicinity to the Olympic Village and IBC/MPC.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] At the back of the stadium, there was a steel scaffold that kept host to the Olympic flame, located in a 4m wide bowl at the top, which also was able to take 550 kg in weight.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] There were also stairs leading to the top, containing 96 steps.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The ceremony began on Tuesday, 6 February at 3:00 p.m., with French president Charles de Gaulle in attendance.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Among the 500 invited guests of honour was IOC president Avery Brundage, the Irani empress Farah Pahlavi, the Danish Princess Margrethe and the Grand Duchess of Luxembourg Joséphine Charlotte.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After the Marseillaise was sung, the French national anthem, cultural performances followed.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The procession of the athletes into the stadium was traditionally led by the Greek team.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The other teams proceeded into the stadium in alphabetical order, starting with West Germany (Allemagne) and then East Germany (Allemagne d'Est).
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The last team out was the hosts, the French team.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Albert Michallon, president of COJO, said in his speech that all athletes and visitors were welcome.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Brundage again recollected Pierre de Coubertin's ideals and expressed the hope of these ideals lead to a peaceful and less materialistic world.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] He invited Charles de Gaulle to open the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] De Gaulle appeared on the stage and read out the opening set-phrase.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] 14 Chasseurs Alpins soldiers carried a giant 54m2 Olympic flag into the stadium and hoisted.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The organisers had decided against the usual tradition of letting the peace dove fly.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Instead, they let out 500 small Olympic flags on paper parachutes and 30,000 perfumed paper roses from three helicopters over the stadium.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Following this, figure skater Alain Calmat was the last torch bearer to enter the stadium.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] He climbed up the steps to the bowl, where his a sound of his heartbeat amplified over the loudspeakers.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Once at the top, he lit the Olympic flame.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Shortly afterwards, skier Léo Lacroix read out the Olympic oath.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] At the end, the Patrouille de France, the aerobatic flight display team, flew over the stadium and marked out the colours of the Olympic rings with their vapour trails in the sky.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The Winter Olympics ended on Sunday, 18 February, with the closing ceremony in the *Ice Stadium*.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The first highlight was the figure skaters gala session.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It also included ice dancing, an event that was first introduced into the main programme eight years after in 1976.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The best ten partners from the last world championship took part in the event and there was no scores.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After that, the last award ceremonies then took place.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After the Marseillaise was played, all athletes who were still in Grenoble reassembled onto the ice and the flag bearers formed a semi-circle.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Whilst the flags of Greece, France and next host Japan were put up, a torchbearer brought the Olympic flame into the stadium and ignited it into a small cauldron on the center of ice.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] IOC president Avery Brundage thanked the organisers and declared the games over.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] When the Olympic flag was lowed and retired from the venue, gun salutes were heard all across the town and finally the flame went out.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] 11-years-old Romanian figure skater Beatrice Huștiu became the youngest female participant at the 1968 Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] She took part in the singles event and finished in 29th place, which was third from bottom.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The youngest male participant was aged 12 years and 110 days.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] He was also a figure skater called Jan Hoffmann, who represented East Germany.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In Grenoble, he finished in 26th place and was also third from bottom.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In 1974 and 1980, he became world champion, and in 1980, he won silver in the Olympic Games at Lake Placid.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] American speed skater Dianne Holum was the youngest medal winner.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] She won silver in the 500m event at the age of 16 years and 266 days.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Two days later, she added a bronze by competing in the 1000m event.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The youngest gold medal winner was also from the United States: 19-year-old figure skater Peggy Fleming.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The oldest medal winner and oldest gold medal winner was 40-year-old Italian Eugenio Monti, who won the gold medal in the four-man bobsleigh team.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Five days before, he had also won the two-man bobsleigh team gold medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The public became more aware of the doping issue during the 1960s.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The first death caused by doping at the Olympic Games occurred in 1960 in Rome, when Danish cyclist Knut Enemark Jensen, who took amphetamines, fell off his bike and died.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It took four years until the IOC recognised the seriousness of the situation and created a medical commission.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] In 1967, the IOC followed the example set by other sport associations and proclaimed a ban on doping.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the first time, doping control was carried out at the 1968 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The IOC tested 86 athletes but all the tests came back negative.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Also in 1967, the IOC decided to carry out gender controls in order to prevent intersex people from competing at women's competitions.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Multiple athletes from Eastern Europe immediately retired after the IOC had decided this, which led to much speculation.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Erik Schinegger, the 1966 female downhill world champion from Austria, was tested a couple of days before the 1968 Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] It turned out Schinegger had been born with internal sex organs doctors had never tested for.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] After learning of this condition, Schinegger ultimately decided to have gender reassignment surgery and legally changed his first name from Erika to Erik.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The media representatives lived in an apartment complex built between April 1966 and October 1967, a few hundred meters away from the Olympic village in Malherbe, a central part of Grenoble.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The complex consisted of seven eight to ten floored towers totaling 637 flats, an underground car park and a school.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The school housed an IBM computer center, a copy center, the studios of French radio and TV broadcaster ORTF and broadcasters from other countries, photo laboratories, and other technical amenities.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The offices of the newspaper and photo journalists, the technicians, and the general administration were situated on the bottom floors of the towers, the other floors serving as accommodation.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The press restaurant was later used as a car park.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] There were also smaller press centers in the Stade de glace in Grenoble, and at the five other venues in Autrans, Chamrousse, L'Alpe d'Huez, Saint-Nizier-du-Moucherotte, and Villard-de-Lans.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The organising committee COJO assigned 1,545 accreditations to the following people: 1,095 went to press, radio and television journalists, 301 to photographers, and 149 to other unnamed groups.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 19 September 1966, COJO signed an exclusive contract with ORTF for the provision of broadcasting on the television to EBU's catchment area and to Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 14 February 1967, the American Broadcasting Company (ABC) received the exclusive broadcasting rights for the United States and Latin America.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] On 15 October 1967, NHK received the rights to broadcast in Japan.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] For the first time in the history of the Olympic Games, the Games were transmitted in colour.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] ORTF installed 25 colour and 37 black and white cameras (ABC had an independent broadcasting system).
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The total broadcasting time lasted 150 hours and 15 mins, 91 hours and 25 mins were in colour.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The total number of viewers was recorded at 600 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] Concerning the question of scoring the men's freestyle figure skating and the unfortunate circumstances of the men's slalom, the *Bild am Sonntag* published the title "Am Ende kam der große Krach" ("At the end there was a great bust-up").
[src:banff-national-park/1968-winter-olympics] The *Münchner Merkur* said they would have tolerated Schranz's disqualification, but the incidents in the figure skating had led to a bitter aftertaste.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] The **1972 Winter Olympics**, officially the **XI Olympic Winter Games** and commonly known as **Sapporo 1972**, were a winter multi-sport event held from February 3 to 13, 1972, in Sapporo, Hokkaido Prefecture, Japan.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] It was the first Winter Olympic Games to take place outside Europe and North America.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] Sapporo first won the rights to host the 1940 Winter Olympics, but Japan resigned as the Games' host after its 1937 invasion of China.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] All the cities awarded Games that were cancelled due to war have since hosted the Games (London, Tokyo, Helsinki, Sapporo and Cortina d'Ampezzo).
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] Sapporo competed with Banff, Lahti, and Salt Lake City.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] The Games were awarded at the 64th IOC Session in Rome, Italy, on April 26, 1966.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] In preparation, the Japanese constructed new largescale facilities at Sapporo and conducted a trial run a full year in advance of the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] An international sport week was held in February, 1971, to assess the city's preparations as well as "to test its civic mettle and hospitality", and this effort was acclaimed by Olympic observers as "a complete success".
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] The development of new infrastructure proved to be a huge boon for the Sapporo economy: by the time of the Games, the national government had invested some US$500 million in upgrades, including a new subway.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] The Games' organizers themselves turned a healthy profit in part because they arranged a record $8.47 million for broadcasting rights with American companies.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] 1 New facilities constructed in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] 2 Existing facilities modified or refurbished in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] 35 nations participated in the 1972 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] The Republic of China (commonly known as Taiwan) and the Philippines participated in their first Winter Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1972-winter-olympics] These are the top eleven nations that won medals at these Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The **1988 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **XV Olympic Winter Games** (French: *XVes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Calgary 1988** were a multi-sport event held from February 13 to 28, 1988, with Calgary, Alberta, as the main host city.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This marks the most recent time that two consecutive Olympic Games were hosted in North America (with the 1984 Summer Olympic Games hosted in Los Angeles, California, United States).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympic Games to be held for 15 days, like the counterpart Summer Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The majority of the events took place in Calgary itself.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the snow events were shared by Nakiska ski resort in Kananaskis Country at the west of the city and the Canmore Nordic Centre Provincial Park in the town of Canmore.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the last Winter Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1988, a record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOC) sent a total of 1,424 athletes to these Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These Winter Olympics would be the last attended for both the Soviet Union and East Germany NOCs.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Just like the 1976 Summer Olympics, host country Canada failed again to win a gold medal on their home soil (they won three gold medals in demonstration events, but these are not included in the official medal table).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Finnish ski jumper, Matti Nykänen, and the Dutch speed skater, Yvonne van Gennip, won three individual gold medals each.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics were also remembered for the "heroic failure" of both the British ski jumper, Michael Edwards, and the debut of the Jamaica national bobsleigh team.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Both of them became subjects of major feature films about their participation in these Games: *Cool Runnings* by Walt Disney Pictures in 1993 and *Eddie the Eagle* by 20th Century Fox in 2016.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At approximately C$829 million, the Calgary Games were the most expensive Olympics ever held at the time, as all the necessary infrastructure was built from scratch.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The facilities that were built for these Winter Olympics helped the host region to turn into the heart of Canada's elite winter sports program, under the tutelage of WinSport.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the Games, their legacy still standing and in constant use, as the five purpose-built venues for those Games are now used for training and hosting various winter sporting events every year.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These policies helped Canada develop into one of the top nations in Winter Olympics competition.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The climax of this effort was the overall first-place finish at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary made its fourth attempt at hosting the Winter Games when it bid for the 1988 Winter Olympic Games, which also marked Canada's seventh bid for the Winter Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Montreal made the first Canadian bid for the Winter Games in 1956 and won the rights to host the 1976 Summer Olympics, and Vancouver made attempts to host the 1976 and 1980 Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary, alongside neighbouring Banff, under the leadership of the Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA), submitted bids for the Winter Games in 1964, 1968, and 1972.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, CODA went dormant in 1966 after losing three consecutive bids.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, Frank King and Bob Niven of Calgary's Booster Club took over the organization's leadership and revived CODA.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King and Niven consulted former Olympic Sprinter and CODA founder, Ernie McCullough, and politician Arthur Ryan Smith, who had worked on previous bids, for guidance on the project.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In October 1979, CODA secured the Canadian Olympic Association's (COA) support for Canada's official bid to host the 1988 Winter Olympics, winning over a competing bid by Vancouver with a vote of 27–9.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary's bid was at the time the most ambitious for the Winter Olympics ever, as the city lacked winter sports facilities and almost everything would have to be built from scratch.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA proposed constructing all new venues, arguing that if Calgary was awarded the Games, Canada's inventory of training facilities would increase significantly.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Vancouver bidding committee argued that Calgary's bid represented a "Big-ticket Games" idea, and estimated to cost nearly three times what Vancouver was expected to pay to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Vancouver's bid was based on already developed infrastructure, including the Expo 86 precinct, the Pacific Coliseum and Whistler Blackcomb, which later served as the basis for the successful 2010 Winter Olympics bid and the later unsuccessful 2030 Winter Olympics bid.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA then spent two years building local support for the megaproject, selling CA$5 memberships to approximately 80,000 of Calgary's 600,000 residents.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary also secured CA$270 million in funding from the federal (CA$200 million) and provincial governments.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Some civic leaders, including then-mayor Ralph Klein, travelled around the world to lobby IOC delegates.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The arrival of the National Hockey League's (NHL) newly relocated Calgary Flames from Atlanta in 1980 drove the city to construct a new multi-use arena that would later be named the Olympic Saddledome, demonstrating to the IOC Calgary's determination to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic bid itself emphasized the unique cultural and natural characteristics who mark the Calgary Metropolitan Region and the Alberta Province and also canadian prairies landscapes, as a perfect places for hosting the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At the bidding documents, the city was marketed with a capitalist, oil-driven and vibrant economy that also had mountain playgrounds, extensive wilderness, and a rodeo culture.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When the two images of Calgary and Alberta were brought together, they seemed to be contrasting; however, they complemented each other as part of extensive and intense bidding lobby process.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary was one of three finalists during the 1988 Winter Olympics bid process.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The other two were Falun, Sweden, and Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Italian town (comune) had before hosted the 1956 Winter Olympics and was seen by many as the favorite.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The vote was held on September 30, 1981, in Baden-Baden, West Germany, during the 84th IOC Session and 11th Olympic Congress.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After Cortina d'Ampezzo was eliminated in the first round of balloting, Calgary won in the second and final round of balloting over Falun, by a margin of 17 votes.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The announcement of CODA's victory sent the delegates in Baden-Baden and Calgary residents into singing and dancing.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also made then Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, burst openly into tears in front of the cameras.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Later, Ralph Klein sang a rendition of Mac Davis' *It's Hard to Be Humble*.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympics awarded to Canada and the second Olympic Games overall, following the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Cortina d'Ampezzo, along with Milan, would get to host the 2026 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pelle noted that once the Games were awarded to Calgary, the cultural and community aspects of the bid were pushed aside by the newly formed Calgary Olympic organizing committee called the *Olympiques Calgary Olympics '88* (OCO'88).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It then proceeded to take on a "vigorous, resilient, and impersonal corporate business strategy" based in the work made by Los Angeles 1984 Organizing Committee (LAOCOG) toward the planning and operation of the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Bill Pratt was a former general contractor who took over as OCO'88 president in 1983.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He was the main manager that oversaw the construction of the Olympic megaproject.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Donald Jacques, a former general manager of the Calgary Exhibition and Stampede, once said, "Because of him, everything was built on time and on budget." However, Bill Pratt was controversial by rubbing many of his colleagues the wrong way.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One former co-worker once predicted back in 1983: "He will get everything built.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There may not be many (of us) left around to enjoy it, but he'll get it done." His relations with the news media were also strained at times.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He had barely settled into his new position when the Calgary press media began criticizing OCO'88 for excessive secrecy and for awarding Olympic contracts to Calgary's PR firm Francis Williams and Johnson Ltd.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pratt was a director of that firm, before accepting the organizing committee job.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 had insisted that there was no conflict of interest involved in the whole process.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Pratt declared: "I have been nailed for a lot, but that does not bother me.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the 1988 Winter Olympics bid was won in 1981, OCO'88 made a new technical assessment and had to re-plan all the originally proposed competition venues except for the few that already existed and were within the campus of the University of Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] McMahon Stadium, the primary outdoor facility used mainly by the Canadian Football League's (CFL) Calgary Stampeders and inside of the University of Calgary and had originally been chosen to host only the opening ceremonies and the Saddledome was chosen to be the place of the closing ceremonies.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] But with the constant revisions of the project, the later addition of 4 more days in competition and mainly the gigantic demands for tickets, the Organizing Committee decided to move the closing ceremony to the Stadium which held twice the capacity of the Saddledome.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The last time that the two Winter Olympic ceremonies were held at the same venue was at the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley, California.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics' five main all-purpose venues were created at a significant cost at that time.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three of them are located within Calgary and the other two are located west of the city.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Olympic Saddledome was planned to be the main venue of the games, hosting ice hockey and figure skating finals.This arena is also part of Stampede Park and was expected to cost C$83 million, but a cost overrun pushed it to nearly C$100 million and caused a nine-month delay.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Second, the Olympic Oval was built on the campus of the University of Calgary for C$40 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Third, Canada Olympic Park (formerly called the *Paskapoo Ski Hill*) was renovated for C$200 million and is located on the western outskirts of Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This most expensive venue of these Winter Olympics hosted the men's bobsleigh, luge, and men's ski jumping and its portion of the Nordic combined events.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, it hosted some events of the demonstration sport of freestyle skiing.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From the west of Calgary, the other two main all-purpose venues were built at the foothills of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Canmore Nordic Centre was 90% funded by the province of Alberta, for C$17.3 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located beside the town of Canmore and it hosted cross-country skiing, plus its men's portion of the Nordic combined, and the men's biathlon events.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was projected that the area could become a year-round destination for Albertans, by facilitating and accelerate Canmore's economic transition away from coal mining to tourist attraction.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the Nakiska (*Cree* meaning "to meet") ski resort was the most controversial and polemic complex built for these Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located on Mount Allan (inside Kananaskis Country) and it hosted the alpine skiing events.It cost around C$25 million to Alberta government funds.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This venue drew a lot of criticisms because of the various environmental concerns, the rejection by International Ski Federation (FIS) of slopes for each of the 10 events in the program and the use of artificial snow due to the lack of natural snow on that season.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the first inspections, the International Ski Federation (FIS) officials noted the venue's lack of technical difficulties needed for the Olympic competition.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, these FIS delegates proposed some major changes in the slopes in an action to cause bigger difficulties.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These modifications were met with praise from Olympic alpine skiing competitors.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Like at Canada Olympic Park, this venue also hosted some freestyle skiing events as a demonstration sport.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three other existing facilities served as secondary competition venues for the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The first one, was the Max Bell Centre hosted the demonstration sports of curling and short track speed skating.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Father David Bauer Olympic Arena and the Stampede Corral shared the functions of secondary venues for the ice hockey tournament and the figure skating preliminaries.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Though the Stampede Corral did not support the International Ice Hockey Federation's (IIHF) standard-sized Olympic ice surface, OCO'88 was able to convince the IIHF to sanction the ice rink for Olympic competition, in exchange for a C$1.2 million payment.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) entered athletes at the 1988 Winter Olympics, with eight more NOCs than any other previous Olympic Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] 1,109 men and 315 women, for a total of 1,424 athletes, participated in these Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Fiji, Guam, Guatemala, Jamaica, the Netherlands Antilles and the Virgin Islands had their Winter Olympics debut in 1988.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There were 46 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, there were 22 events in 4 demonstration sports and disciplines that have no official status in the overall medal tally.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather conditions were a problem facing OCO'88 during the Games, with temperatures ranging from −28 to 22 °C (−18 to 72 °F).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After an unexpectedly freezing opening ceremony, the outdoor competitions scheduled to start the next day had to be postponed.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This ended up affecting the men's downhill skiing event at Nakiska which was postponed for one day, due to Chinook winds blowing up to 160 km/h.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The women's downhill event also experienced the same scenario.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] With the ski jumping venue facing north at Canada Olympic Park (COP), the same winds also disrupted those events, with the large hill event being postponed four times.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also disrupted the Nordic combined events, in which the ski jumping part had to be postponed as well.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This situation ended up causing something unprecedented in the history of the Winter Olympics, as for the first time both the ski jumping and Nordic combined cross-country skiing events were contested in a single day.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite using artificial cooling, the bobsleigh and luge events did not need to be rescheduled; however, several races had to be postponed because of the high temperatures recorded and also because of the dirt that was carried away by these winds.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA) Board of Directors had originally 25 members.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was chaired by Frank King, followed by former Mayors Ralph Klein and Ross Alger, and other prominent Calgarians.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The executive committee president was Robert Niven.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic Organizing Committee (OOC) was formed by utilizing many of the original board of directors members.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was initially started with 11 members and was grown to 25 members by October 1983.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It grew further to 29 members by 1985, when former Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, was added to the list.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] An Olympic biographer, Kevin Wamsley, noted that the CEO Frank King, President Bill Pratt, Ralph Klein, and former COA President Roger Jackson had collectively the most influence on all aspects of these Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This organizing committee took a hierarchical form for planning these Olympics, which caused consternation from some staff, volunteers, and people in executive roles.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The original staff, who were at odds with the current management structure, were either fired or willingly resigned.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, there were claims that some of the volunteers were verbally abused.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As a result, David Leighton resigned as OOC President in 1982, after only five months on the job.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Bill Pratt, a former general manager of the Calgary Stampede, became the new OCOG's president shortly afterwards.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The City of Calgary and the Canadian Olympic Association (COA) delegated officially all Olympic responsibilities, including staging the Winter Olympics under the Olympic Charter, to the newly formed OCO'88 in February and September 1983 respectively.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, conflicts within OCO'88 grew in the public eye and a review of the entire management structure was conducted after Ralph Klein threatened it with a public inquiry in 1986.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Thus, Frank King remained as CEO, but with the addition of more full-time staff.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, more than 9,000 volunteers were registered who were allocated to the most diverse areas.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite these changes, there was still some animosity within OCO'88.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Kevin Walmsley noted that Bill Pratt and Frank King continued to have a very tense relationship and that any movement caused sparks with each other.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games coincided with a shift in television policy by the International Olympic Committee and growing enthusiasm by broadcasters in the United States.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Amendments to the *Olympic Charter* in 1977 established a policy mandating joint television rights involving the IOC and the local organizing committee and was enshrined in the 1981 bid agreement for the Calgary games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The joint negotiating committee convened in 1984 late-January, some weeks before the Sarajevo 1984 Winter Games at the IOC's president residency at the Lausanne Palace were held to negotiate the Calgary television contracts with American broadcasters.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiating committee was represented by Dick Pound for the IOC, Bill Wardle for OCO'88 and consultant Barry Frank.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The co-negotiating committee designed a new tender process for the television rights bid with an emphasis on creating a level playing field for all broadcasters.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time, the negotiations were based on a series of sealed bids and representatives from ABC, CBS and NBC vied for the opportunity to broadcast the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After six rounds of sealed bids, the ABC delegation led by producer Roone Arledge was successful with an agreement paying a record US$309 million (CA$386 million Canadian at the time) in exchange for exclusive rights for the games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CBS exited the bidding process after the second round with a final offer of $257 million, while ABC and NBC both reached the fifth round with an offer of $300 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the sixth and final stage, the IOC and OCO'88 decided a coin flip would determine which of ABC or NBC had the right to submit the first bid or defer, a decision neither network supported.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Watson elected to call the coin-flip, although he remained silent on the first flip, so a second coinflip was required, and NBC won with a choice of "heads", and after 30 minutes of deliberation submitted a $304 million bid.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's representative Arledge made a quick phone call to executive Fred Pierce, and ABC submitted a $309 million bid, exceeding NBC's bid by $5 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's record-setting bid was immediately controversial, first Arledge had exceeded the maximum allowable bid set by ABC's executives by $34 million, and in the coming weeks ABC's coverage of the 1984 Winter Olympics which cost $91.5 million returned poor Nielsen ratings.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Early estimates speculated the network would lose $50-$60 million televising the games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* described the NBC agreement as the "biggest prize of the Winter Olympics".
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The deal which was at the time the highest amount ever paid for a sporting event, allowed OCO'88 to announce the Games would be debt-free.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiations with American television broadcasters were in sharp contrast to negotiations for Western European rights with the European Broadcasting Union quickly closing an exclusive deal with the IOC for US$5.7 million led by Juan Antonio Samaranch and Marc Hodler on behalf of the IOC.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The *Calgary Herald* headline after the announcement negatively reflected on the "bargain" the European network received, and OCO'88 chairman Frank King publicly expressed his disappointment with the IOC.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Samaranch's argument for providing for a privileged negotiation with EBU was ensuring European viewers had equal access and coverage of the games, something he did not believe would occur if private networks from each nation were provided with the opportunity to bid.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dick Pound was also critical of the decision and argued more revenue could be brought in from BBC and RAI alone and the privileged status suppressed the willingness of the EBU to make a market-value bid on the games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CTV Television Network won the bid to broadcast the Games in Canada in December 1983, paying CA$4.5 million for the exclusive rights.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CTV also won the $23.5 million contract to serve as the host broadcaster, responsible for the manpower and equipment to televise the games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, while the bid was strengthened, CBC and CTV signed an agreement that if Calgary were the eventual winner, the two broadcasters would create a consortium in which the purchase of television rights would take place jointly.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The previous arrangement had CBC provide full coverage for Summer Games with CTV broadcasting a nightly summary, while CTV had the rights to Winter Games with CBC broadcasting a nightly summary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The nightly summary of the Games was also televised on CBC.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Japan's broadcast rights were awarded to NHK in July 1986 for US$3.9 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 made several alterations to the Olympic program as part of efforts to ensure value for its broadcast partners.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Now, the premier and main events, including ice hockey and figure skating, were scheduled for prime time and the Games were lengthened to 15 days from the previous 12 to ensure three weekends of coverage.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, a significant downturn in advertising revenue for sporting events resulted in ABC forecasting significant financial losses on the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary organizers appreciated their fortunate timing in signing the deal.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King described the timing of the contract with ABC as "the passing of the sun and the moon at the right time for Calgary".
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The revenue growth from broadcasting was significant for the Calgary Games, OCO'88 generated $324.9 million in broadcast rights, which was a significant growth over an eight-period (the 1980 Lake Placid Games generated US$20.7 million).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC had net losses of more than $60 million, and broadcast rights to the 1992 Winter Olympics were later sold to the CBS network for $243 million, a 20 per cent reduction compared to Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A series of ticket-related scandals plagued the organizing committee as the Games approached, resulting in widespread public anger.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Demand for tickets was high, particularly for the main events which had sold out a year in advance.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Residents had been promised that only 10 per cent of tickets would go to "Olympic insiders", IOC officials and sponsors, but OCO'88 was later forced to admit that up to 50 percent of seats to top events had gone to insiders.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The organizing committee, which was subsequently chastised by mayor Klein for running a "closed shop", admitted that it had failed to properly communicate the obligations it had to supply IOC officials and sponsors with priority tickets.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At that time, the American dollar was trading 40 cents higher than the Canadian dollar, resulting in significantly higher than anticipated revenue through currency conversion.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The ticket manager maintained his innocence claiming he was used as a scapegoat and sponsor credit card Visa was responsible for the error, despite his claims, the ticketing manager was convicted of fraud, theft, and forgery, and sentenced to 5 years in prison.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Organizers attempted to respond to public concern by asking sponsors to consider reducing their orders and by paying $1.5 million to add 2,600 seats to the Saddledome, as well as increase capacity for ski jumping, alpine skiing and the opening ceremonies.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This led to a change of the venue of the closing ceremonies from Saddledome to McMahon Stadium, as the stadium capacity was about two times bigger than the indoor venue.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King also noted that the Calgary Games offered a then-record 1.9 million tickets for sale, three times the amount available at Sarajevo or Lake Placid and that 79 percent of them were to be allocated to Calgarians.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] By the start of the 1988 Winter Games, a record of over 1.4 million tickets had been sold, a figure that eclipsed the previous three Winter Games combined.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the OCO'88's final report, the Committee admits the culmination of fraud charges, a large portion of premier tickets requested by Olympic insiders, and poor communications led to a negative public reaction to the ticketing process.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time in the history of the Olympics, both summer and winter, the Organizing Committee worked with a refund policy for returned or unused tickets.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When an event was postponed by at least 24 hours, the ticketholder was eligible for a refund.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Due to weather issues, the 8 events that were scheduled for the first 24 hours had to be rescheduled, resulting in 130,000 ticket refunds totalling CA$2.9 million, with transactions handled by the Royal Bank of Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The city of Calgary is world-renowned for the enthusiasm of its population for volunteer work which is reflected in the annual Calgary Stampede, which also relied heavily on volunteers to run the Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Over 22,000 people signed up for more than 9,400 positions, no matter how inglorious: doctors, lawyers and executives even offered to collect the waste generated during the opening ceremony.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, for the first time, a "Homestay" program was created and several local families opened their homes to visitors from around the world, and others were renting their rooms or houses to those who could not stay in pay a reserve in a hotel.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Klein was among those who felt it necessary that the event be community driven, a decision which allowed the city's welcoming spirit to manifest.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games' mascots, Hidy and Howdy, were designed to evoke images of "western hospitality".
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The smiling, cowboy-themed polar bears were popular across Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Played by a team of 150 students from Bishop Carroll High School, the sister-brother pair made up to 300 appearances per month in the lead-up to the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From their introduction at the closing ceremonies of the Sarajevo Games in 1984 until their retirement at the conclusion of the Calgary Games, the pair made about 50,000 appearances.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The iconic mascots graced signs welcoming travellers to Calgary for nearly two decades until they were replaced in 2007.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The mascot's names "Hidy" and "Howdy" were chosen by a public contest.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games were the most expensive Games, summer or winter, to be held at that time, with total expenses exceeding CA$879.6 million.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The high cost was anticipated, as organizers were aware at the outset of their bid that most facilities would have to be constructed.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The venues, constructed primarily with public money, were designed to have lasting use beyond the Games and were planned to become the home of several of Canada's national winter sports teams.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The record-breaking cost of the Calgary Olympics came in stark contrast to the original projections during the 1981 bid, which estimated a total cost of CA$218 million, split between CA$126 million in capital costs and CA$92 million in operating costs.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The significant growth in capital expenditures came despite the three levels of government taking over projects which constituted nearly half of the original budgeted capital projects.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Of the total expenses for the Games (CA$879.6 million), the Government of Canada contributed CA$200 million (22.7 per cent), the Government of Alberta contributed CA$130 million (14.8 per cent), and the City of Calgary contributed CA$43 million (4.9 per cent).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CA$320.8 million of government capital contributions not directly included in OCO'88's revenue statements included the Government of Canada constructing the CA$72.2 million Canada Olympic Park, and CA$40 million for the Olympic Oval.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Provincial expenses included CA$14.4 million to build the Canmore Nordic Centre, and CA$25.3 million to build Nakiska.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All three governments contributed to the CA$97.7 million Olympic Saddledome.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were a major economic boom for the city, which had fallen into its worst recession in 40 years following the collapse of both oil and grain prices three years before the games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A report prepared for the city in January 1985 estimated the games would create 11,100 man-years of employment and generate CA$450 million in salaries and wages.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In its post-Games report, OCO'88 estimated the Olympics created CA$1.4 billion in economic benefits across Canada during the 1980s, 70 percent within Alberta, as a result of capital spending, increased tourism and new sporting opportunities created by the facilities.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Olympic torch relay began on November 15, 1987, when the torch was lit at Olympia and Greek runner Stelios Bisbas began what was called "the longest torch run in history".
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's, Newfoundland on the Atlantic Ocean two days later and over 88 days, travelled west across the then 10 Canadian provinces and two territories.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It passed through most major cities, north to the Arctic Ocean at Inuvik, Northwest Territories, then west to the Pacific Ocean at Victoria, British Columbia before returning east to Alberta, and finally Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch covered a distance of 18,000 kilometres (11,000 mi), the greatest distance for a torch relay in Olympic history until the 2000 Sydney Games, and a sharp contrast to the 1976 Montreal Games when the relay covered only 775 kilometres (482 mi).
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The identity of the final torchbearer who would light the Olympic cauldron was one of the Organizing Committee's most closely guarded secrets.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's with Barbara Ann Scott and Ferd Hayward representing Canada's past Olympians and ended with Ken Read and Cathy Priestner carrying the torch into McMahon Stadium representing the nation's current Olympians.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The design of the Olympic Torch for the Calgary games was a reproduction of the main landmark building of the Calgary skyline, the Calgary Tower.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The National Research Council Canada developed the design for the Torch, the base of the torch is made of maple wood, the national tree of Canada, aluminum, and hardened steel, all 100% collected in Canadian territory.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch was designed to remain lit despite the extreme conditions of Canadian winters.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Torch had to be light enough for relay runners to carry comfortably, and the final design came in at 60 centimetres in length and 1.7 kilograms in weight.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The maple handle portion included laser-incised pictograms of the 10 official Olympic Winter sports, and lettering was engraved on the steel caldron portion.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch used a mixed type of three fuels (gasoline, kerosene and alcohol) to allow a continuous burn during the unpredictable Canadian winter.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Approximately 100 torches were manufactured for the Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Governor General Jeanne Sauvé opened the Games on behalf of Queen Elizabeth II as an estimated 1.5 billion people watched the ceremony.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather was a dominant story throughout much of the Games, as strong chinook winds that brought daily temperatures as high as 17 °C (63 °F) wreaked havoc on the schedules for outdoor events.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Events were delayed when winds were deemed unsafe for competitors and organizers used artificial snow making equipment to ensure skiing venues were properly prepared.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first time in Olympic history that alpine events were held on artificial snow.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were also marred by the death of the Austrian ski team's doctor, Joerg Oberhammer, on February 25 after a collision with another skier threw him underneath a working snow grooming machine at Nakiska, crushing and killing him instantly.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The top individual competitors at the Olympics were Finnish ski jumper Matti Nykänen and Dutch speed skater Yvonne van Gennip as they each won three gold medals.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Italy's Alberto Tomba won gold in two skiing events, his first of five career Olympic medals en route to becoming the first alpine skier to win medals at three Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] East Germany's Katarina Witt defended her 1984 gold medal in women's figure skating, capturing a second gold in Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Her compatriot Christa Rothenburger won the gold medal in the 1000 metre race in speed skating, then went on to win a silver medal in the team sprint cycling event at the 1988 Summer Games to become the only person in Olympic history to win medals at both Olympic Games in the same year.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won gold in ice hockey as Nordic neighbours Finland and Sweden took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As it had in 1976, Canada again failed to win an official gold medal as the host of an Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canadians won two gold medals in demonstration events, including by Sylvie Daigle as one of her five medals in short-track speed skating.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canada's top official performances came in figure skating where Brian Orser and Elizabeth Manley each won silver medals.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Boitano won the gold medal over Orser by one-tenth of a point.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Witt won the gold while Thomas won the bronze medal.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Manley was not viewed as a medal contender, but skated the greatest performance of her career to come within a fraction of Witt's gold medal-winning score.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] American speed skater Dan Jansen's personal tragedy was one of the more poignant events of the Games as he skated the 500 metre race mere hours after his sister Jane died of leukemia.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A gold medal favourite, Jansen chose to compete as he felt it is what his sister would have wanted.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Viewers around the world witnessed his heartbreak as he fell and crashed into the outer wall in the first quarter of his heat.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the 1000 metre race four days later, Jansen was on a world record pace when he again fell.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After failing again in Albertville, Jansen finally won a gold medal at the 1994 Lillehamer Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One of the most popular athletes from the games was British ski jumper Michael Edwards, who gained infamy by placing last in both the 70 and 90 metre events finishing 70 and 53 points behind his next closest competitor, respectively.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Edwards' "heroic failure" made him an instant celebrity; he went from earning £6,000 per year as a plasterer before the Games to making £10,000 per hour per appearance afterward.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Left embarrassed by the spectacle he created, the IOC altered the rules following Calgary to eliminate each nation's right to send at least one athlete and set minimum competition standards for future events.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Regardless, the President of the Organizing Committee, Frank King, playfully saluted Edwards' unorthodox sporting legacy, which would also be commemorated with a 2016 feature film, *Eddie the Eagle*.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Jamaican bobsleigh team, making their nation's Winter Olympic debut, was also popular in Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The team was the brainchild of a pair of Americans who recruited individuals with strong sprinting ability from the Jamaican military to form the team.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dudley Stokes and Michael White finished the two-man event in 30th place out of 41 competitors and launched the Jamaican team into worldwide fame.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The pair, along with Devon Harris and Chris Stokes, crashed in the four-man event, but were met with cheers from the crowd as they pushed their sled across the finish line.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Their odyssey was made into the 1993 movie *Cool Runnings*, a largely fictionalized comedy by Walt Disney Pictures.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All of the long track world (WR) and Olympic records (OR) that occurred during these Games were later broken at succeeding Winter Olympics and other world events.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Prior to 1988, the Winter Olympics were viewed as a second-rate event, in comparison to the Summer Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The IOC had, at one point, considered eliminating it altogether.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] First, there are only a few mountainous areas in the world that would be able to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Second, there were major challenges in generating revenues for the host city and the IOC from such Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, CODA convinced the IOC that it could not only generate enough revenues to make a profit but have enough money left over to ensure a lasting legacy of winter sports development.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] OCO'88 followed mainly the example of LAOOC which organized the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Under LAOOC's president, Peter Ueberroth, he was able to attract a large United States television contract and Los Angeles became the first Olympic host city to make a profit.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 1988 Winter Olympics, OCO'88 attracted financial support from over two dozen major Canadian and multinational corporations, in order to generate millions of dollars in revenues.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For OCO'88, it foresaw some winter sports, like the debut of the Super-G and other new winter sports events, as a way to increase the audience's appeal of the Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Thus, for the sponsors, the Games' length of time to 15 days provided an extra weekend of Olympic media coverage to the world.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This additional programming time was filled mainly by TV-friendly demonstration events that are popular in Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The 1988 Winter Olympics' exposure to curling, freestyle skiing, and short track speed skating events in Calgary influenced the worldwide popularity of all of them.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] So much so that all these events became the new and official Olympic finals in the period between the 1992 Winter Olympics to the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Hosting the Winter Olympics helped fuel a significant increase in Calgary's reputation on the world stage.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Crosbie Cotton, a reporter for the *Calgary Herald* who covered the city's Olympic odyssey from its 1979 initiative to the closing ceremonies, noted an increased positive outlook of the city's population over time.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] He believed that the populace began to outgrow its "giant inferiority complex" that is "typically Canadian", by replacing it with a new level of confidence as the Games approached.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This outcome helped the city grow from a regional oil and gas centre, best known for the Calgary Stampede, to a destination for international political, economic, and sporting events.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] A study prepared for the organizing committee of the 2010 Winter Olympics, (VANOC), claimed that Calgary hosted over 200 national and international sporting competitions between 1987 and 2007, due to the facilities it had constructed for these Olympic Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The Games' enduring popularity within Calgary has been attributed to efforts in making them "everybody's Games." Aside from the sense of community fostered by the high level of volunteer support, OCO'88 included the general public in other ways.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For example, the citizens were given an opportunity to purchase a brick with their names engraved on it.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Those bricks were used to build the Olympic Plaza, where the medal ceremonies were held in 1988.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It remains a popular public park and event site in the city's downtown core today.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After the success of these Olympic Games, Calgary was wanting to bring back the Olympic experience again.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It offered, to the IOC, in becoming a possible alternate host city of the 2002 Winter Olympics, after a bidding scandal resulted in speculation that Salt Lake City would not be able to remain the host city.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Next, the city was attempting to be Canada's bid for the 2010 Winter Olympics, but the COC decided to give it to Vancouver and Whistler.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Later, a 2013 *Calgary Sun* online poll found that 81% of respondents said they would support the idea of hosting another Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 13, 2018, Calgary held a public non-binding plebiscite on whether it should bid to host the 2026 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 19, 2018, the results of the plebiscite showed that 56.4% (171,750) of eligible voters said "No", while 43.6% (132,832) of them said "Yes." Therefore, the city council concluded that the bid would be withdrawn.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] In light of the 1976 Summer Olympics' disastrous financial legacy, the Calgary Olympic organizing committee, OCO'88, parlayed its ability to generate television and sponsorship revenues, along with the three levels of government support, into what was ultimately a C$170 million surplus.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] While OCO'88 reported officially a surplus after the Games were over, the accounting practices of the final report did not include federal, provincial, and municipal capital and operations funding infrastructures.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The overall surplus was turned into endowment funds that were split between Canada Olympic Park (C$110 million) and CODA.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] They were subsequently reformed later, in order to manage the Olympic facilities with a trust fund that had grown steadily to be worth over C$200 million by 2013.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Consequently, all five primary facilities built for the 1988 Winter Olympics remained operational for their intended purposes, 25 years after the Games concluded.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Calgary and Canmore became the heart of winter sports in Canada, as CODA (now known as WinSport) established itself as the nation's leader in developing elite winter athletes.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 2006 Winter Olympics, a quarter of Canada's Olympic winter athletes were from the Calgary region and three-quarters of its medalists were from or trained in Alberta.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Before 1988, Canada was not a winter sports power.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The nation's five overall medals won in Calgary was its second-best total at a Winter Olympics, behind the seven overall medals it won at the 1932 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid, New York.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After 1988, Canada won an increasing number of gold and overall medals at each successive Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It culminated in an overall performance of 26 medals won at the 2010 Winter Olympics, which included the previous Olympic record of 14 gold medals.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Until 2010, Norway won the most Olympic gold medals on home soil at the 1952 Winter Olympics.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, Norway recaptured the record of winning the most Olympic gold medals at a single Winter Olympics in 2022, claiming 16.
[src:banff-national-park/1988-winter-olympics-p02] At the 2018 Winter Olympics, Canada earned its highest overall medal count in the Winter Olympics to date, with a total of 29 medals.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The **Abbot Pass hut** was an alpine hut located at an altitude of 2,925 metres (9,596 ft) in Abbot Pass in the Rocky Mountains in Alberta, Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] It was nestled between Mount Victoria and Mount Lefroy, straddling the Great Divide, which, in this region, defines the boundary between Banff National Park in Alberta and Yoho National Park in British Columbia.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] While close to the border, the hut lay entirely in Banff National Park, and was the second-highest permanently habitable structure in Canada (after the Neil Colgan Hut).
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The hut was maintained by the Alpine Club of Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Abbot Pass hut was declared a National Heritage site in 1992.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] It was closed in the summer of 2018 pending a geotechnical evaluation of the slope which underlay the structure, after a hiker noticed erosion on its eastern side, due to melting glacier ice.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The COVID-19 pandemic delayed repair work; by the time work was able to begin again, the hut was deemed irreparable.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The pass and the hut are named after Philip Stanley Abbot (1867 - 1896), who became the first mountaineering fatality in North America after he fell in an attempt to make the first ascent of Mount Lefroy in 1896.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The hut was built in 1922 by Swiss guides working for the Canadian Alpine Association to shelter clients attempting to climb Victoria and Lefroy.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Much of the construction material was carried from Lake Louise on horseback across the Victoria Glacier and winched or carried on guides' backs up the pass on a route known as *The Deathtrap* because of its exposure to avalanches and crevasses.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The CAC operated the hut for 40 years, and in the 1960s turned the operation over to Parks Canada, which renovated it with the help of volunteers.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] In 1985, the park service turned the hut over to the Alpine Club of Canada, which renovated it several times.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The hut was designated Abbot Pass Refuge Cabin National Historic Site of Canada in 1992, and, in 1997, a federal plaque was placed outside its front door.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Because many guests of the Chateau Lake Louise were trying mountaineering for the first time, Edward Feuz, a Swiss guide, suggested that the CPR build a rest stop between Lake Louise and the hut.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] In 1924 the Plain of Six Glaciers Tea House was built to accommodate overnight guests.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Abbot Pass (and the hut) may be approached from either the Lake O'Hara area on the British Columbia side (hiking past Lake Oesa), or the more technically demanding route from Lake Louise on the Alberta side.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The hut was rarely used in winter due to avalanche hazard.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The approach via Lake O'Hara was by far the most popular route to the hut.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] It was safer and less technical than going in via *the Deathtrap* or the *Fuhrmann Ledges*.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] It involved about 900 metres (3,000 feet) of elevation gain and 3 to 5+ hours from Lake O'Hara to the hut depending on conditions and the strength of the party.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Some groups were caught out overnight on the trail or stranded at the hut in bad weather conditions.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The first hurdle on this approach was getting on the bus to Lake O'Hara.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The bus is operated by Parks Canada and is used to control the number of people going to Lake O'Hara.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Reservations are difficult to obtain; however an automatic reservation on the bus could be obtained by booking a reservation at the Abbot Pass hut with the Alpine Club of Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The alternative was to walk 10 km up the access road carrying all equipment.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] From Lake O'Hara, people going to the hut could follow the signed hiking trails to Lake Oesa to a sign marking the end of the Parks Canada trail, at which point it became largely scrambling.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] A trail was built to the hut by the Alpine Club, but parts of it were sometimes erased by rockslides, so route finding skills are helpful.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] A helmet is a good safety precaution in case of rockfall, and an ice axe in case of ice or snow on the trail.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] One avalanche fatality occurred on the route, so it should not be undertaken when avalanches are possible.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The route from Lake Louise involves significant objective hazards.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] A broad path leads from the Chateau Lake Louise along the lake shore past the teahouse and on to the Plain of Six Glaciers.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] It then continues into the deep gorge between Mount Victoria and Mount Lefroy - known as **The Deathtrap**.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Persons going through this should move rapidly in case of serac fall or avalanches from the glaciers above.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] It involves crossing a number of crevasses in the glacier and may be impassible due to wall-to-wall bergschrund at the upper end.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] This is not an attractive route and should only be attempted by strong alpinists when there is deep snow cover on the glacier.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The hut was often used as a base for alpine climbing on Mount Victoria and Mount Lefroy (both over 3400 metres / 11,000 feet), and as a destination in itself for ambitious hikers.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] One of the reasons for the popularity of the hut was that climbers can ascend both Victoria and Lefroy in a weekend.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The normal route up Mount Lefroy (3423 m / 11,230 ft) is via the west face, going straight up the slopes from the hut toward the summit.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] There are routes up three separate gullies from the hut.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The choice of the best one depends on snow conditions.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The most popular route up Mount Victoria 3,464 m (11,365 ft) is from the hut via the southeast ridge to the south summit.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Another popular route is a traverse of Mount Victoria, which can be done in either direction, either to or from the hut.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] The hut slept 24 on its upper floor, and had both a wood stove for heating and drying, and a propane system for cooking and lighting.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] Wood and propane were flown in annually by helicopter, by the Alpine Club of Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass-hut] There was a drum-type outhouse a short distance from the hut and human waste was flown out by helicopter.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass] Abbot Pass has a stone hut, built in 1922 by Swiss guides working for the Canadian Pacific Railway, and was maintained by the Alpine Club of Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass] In 2022, the hut was removed by Parks Canada due to erosion making the structure unsafe.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass] Based on the Köppen climate classification, Abbot Pass is located in a subarctic climate zone with cold, snowy winters, and mild summers.
[src:banff-national-park/abbot-pass] Winter temperatures can drop below −20 °C with wind chill factors below −30 °C.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Abraham Lake has a surface area of 53.7 km2 (20.7 sq mi) and a length of 32 km (20 mi).
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Although man-made, the lake has the blue color of other glacial lakes in the Rocky Mountains, which is caused by rock flour.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Abraham Mountain, Elliott Peak, and the Cline River Heliport are located on the western shore of the lake.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Mount Michener is situated on the eastern shore.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Mount Ernest Ross lies at the southern tip of the lake.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Abraham Lake was created by the former Calgary Power Company, now TransAlta, in 1972, with the construction of the Bighorn Dam.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Planning of the dam involved no evaluation of the social and environmental effects it may have caused and no public hearings were held prior to the construction.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Construction of the Bighorn Dam flooded the Kootenay Plains and stopped the livelihood (hunting and fur trapping) of the Bighorn band of the Stoney Nakoda First Nation that had lived in that area.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] It had flooded their cabins, graves and pastures.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] The lake was built on the upper course of the North Saskatchewan River, in the foothills of the Canadian Rockies, and lines David Thompson Highway between Saskatchewan River Crossing and Nordegg.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] The Government of Alberta sponsored a contest to name the lake in February 1972, during the final stages of construction of the Bighorn Dam.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Students across the province were asked to submit names taking into consideration "historical significance, prominent persons, geography and topography, and the value of the lake." It was eventually named after Silas Abraham (c.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] 1870 – 1964), of the Stoney Nakoda First Nation and originally from Morley, Alberta.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] He was a farmer and hunter who lived in the Kootenay Plains and later on the Big Horn 144A reserve.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Trapped methane causes frozen bubbles to form under the ice on the lake's surface.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] This phenomenon results when decaying plants on the lake bed release methane gas, which creates bubbles that become trapped within the ice, in suspended animation, just below the surface as the lake begins to freeze.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] The visual effects formed by the resulting stacks of bubbles, frozen while rising toward the surface, combined with the clear blue water, have made Abraham Lake a popular destination for photographers and nature observers.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] The ice coverage of the lakes varies throughout the winter.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Abraham Lake is usually frozen by late December.
[src:banff-national-park/abraham-lake] Ideal viewing of the ice bubble season is from mid-January to mid-February.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The mountains were formed from sedimentary rocks that were pushed east over newer rock strata, between 80 million and 55 million years ago.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Over the past few million years, glaciers have at times covered most of the park; today they are found only on the mountain slopes, though they include the Columbia Icefield, the largest uninterrupted glacial mass in the Rockies.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Erosion from water and ice have carved the mountains into their current shapes.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Archaeological evidence at Vermilion Lakes indicates presence of Indigenous peoples for more than 10,000 years in the Banff area.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Canadian Pacific Railway was instrumental in Banff's early years, building the Banff Springs Hotel and Chateau Lake Louise, and attracting tourists through extensive advertising.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the early 20th century, roads were built in Banff, at times by war internees from World War I, and through Great Depression-era public works projects.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Icefields Parkway extends from Lake Louise, connecting to Jasper National Park in the north.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since the 1960s, park accommodations have been open all year, with annual tourism visits to Banff increasing to over 5 million in the 1990s.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Millions more pass through the park on the Trans-Canada Highway.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] As Banff has over three million visitors annually, the health of its ecosystem has been threatened.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the mid-1990s, Parks Canada responded by initiating a two-year study which resulted in management recommendations and new policies that aim to preserve ecological integrity.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park has a subarctic climate with three ecoregions, including montane, subalpine, and alpine.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The forests are dominated by lodgepole pine at lower elevations and Engelmann spruce in higher ones below the treeline, above which is primarily rocks and ice.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Mammal species such as the grizzly bear, cougar, wolverine, elk, bighorn sheep and moose are found, along with hundreds of bird species.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Reptiles and amphibians are also found, but only a limited number of species have been recorded.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Throughout its history, Banff National Park has been shaped by tension between conservationist and land exploitation interests.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The park was established on November 25, 1885, as Banff Hot Springs Reserve, in response to conflicting claims over who discovered hot springs there and who had the right to develop the hot springs for commercial interests.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The conservationists prevailed when Prime Minister John A.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Macdonald set aside the hot springs as a small protected reserve, which was later expanded to include Lake Louise and other areas extending north to the Columbia Icefield.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Archaeological evidence found at Vermilion Lakes indicates the first human activity in Banff to 10,300 BP.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Prior to European contact, the area that is now Banff National Park was home to many Indigenous Peoples, including the Stoney Nakoda, Ktunaxa, Tsuut'ina, Kainaiwa, Piikani, Siksika, and Plains Cree.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Indigenous peoples utilized the area to hunt, fish, trade, travel, survey and practice culture.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Many areas within Banff National Park are still known by their Stoney Nakoda names such as Lake Minnewanka and the Waputik Range.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Cave and Basin served as an important cultural and spiritual site for the Stoney Nakoda.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With the admission of British Columbia to Canada on July 20, 1871, Canada agreed to build a transcontinental railroad.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Construction of the railroad began in 1875, with Kicking Horse Pass chosen, over the more northerly Yellowhead Pass, as the route through the Canadian Rockies.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Ten years later, on November 7, 1885, the last spike was driven in Craigellachie, British Columbia.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With conflicting claims over the discovery of hot springs in Banff, Prime Minister John A.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Macdonald decided to set aside a small reserve of 26 square kilometres (10 sq mi) around the hot springs at Cave and Basin as a public park known as the *Banff Hot Springs Reserve* in 1885.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Under the *Rocky Mountains Park Act*, enacted on June 23, 1887, the park was expanded to 674 km2 (260 sq mi) and named *Rocky Mountains Park*.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] This was Canada's first national park, and the third established in North America, after Yellowstone and Mackinac National Parks.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Canadian Pacific Railway built the Banff Springs Hotel and Lake Louise Chalet to attract tourists and increase the number of rail passengers.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Stoney Nakoda First Nation were removed from Banff National Park between the years 1890 and 1920.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The park was designed to appeal to sportsmen, and tourists.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The exclusionary policy met the goals of sports hunting, tourism, and game conservation, as well as of those attempting to "civilize" the First Nations of the area.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Early on, Banff was popular with wealthy European and American tourists, the former of which arrived in Canada via trans-Atlantic luxury liner and continued westward on the railroad.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Some visitors participated in mountaineering activities, often hiring local guides.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Guides Jim and Bill Brewster founded one of the first outfitters in Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] From 1906, the Alpine Club of Canada organized climbs, hikes and camps in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] By 1911, Banff was accessible by automobile from Calgary.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Beginning in 1916, the Brewsters offered motorcoach tours of Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1920, access to Lake Louise by road was available, and the Banff-Windermere Road opened in 1923 to connect Banff with British Columbia.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1902, the park was expanded to cover 11,400 km2 (4,400 sq mi), encompassing areas around Lake Louise, and the Bow, Red Deer, Kananaskis, and Spray rivers.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Bowing to pressure from grazing and logging interests, the size of the park was reduced in 1911 to 4,663 km2 (1,800 sq mi), eliminating many eastern foothills areas from the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Park boundaries changed several more times up until 1930, when the area of Banff was fixed at 6,697 km2 (2,586 sq mi), with the passage of the *National Parks Act*.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The act, which took effect May 30, 1930, also renamed the park *Banff National Park*, named for the Canadian Pacific Railway station, which in turn was named after the Banffshire region in Scotland.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With the construction of a new east gate in 1933, Alberta transferred 0.84 km2 (0.32 sq mi) to the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] This, along with other minor changes in the park boundaries in 1949, set the area of the park at 6,641 km2 (2,564 sq mi).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1877, the First Nations of the area signed Treaty 7, which gave Canada rights to explore the land for resources.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] At the beginning of the 20th century, coal was mined near Lake Minnewanka in Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] For a brief period, a mine operated at Anthracite but was shut down in 1904.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Bankhead mine, at Cascade Mountain, was operated by the Canadian Pacific Railway from 1903 to 1922.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1926, the town was dismantled, with many buildings moved to the town of Banff and elsewhere.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] During World War I, immigrants from Austria-Hungary and Germany were sent to Banff to work in internment camps.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The main camp was at Castle Mountain, and was moved to Cave and Basin during winter.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Much early infrastructure and road construction was done by men of various Slavic origins although Ukrainians constituted a majority of those held in Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1931, the Government of Canada enacted the *Unemployment and Farm Relief Act* which provided public works projects in the national parks during the Great Depression.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In Banff, workers constructed a new bathhouse and pool at Upper Hot Springs to supplement Cave and Basin.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Other projects involved road building in the park, tasks around the Banff townsite and construction of a highway connecting Banff and Jasper.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1934, the*Public Works Construction Act* was passed, providing continued funding for the public works projects.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] New projects included construction of a new registration facility at Banff's east gate and construction of an administrative building in Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] By 1940, the Icefields Parkway reached the Columbia Icefield area of Banff and connected Banff and Jasper.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Most of the infrastructure present in the national park dates from public work projects enacted during the Great Depression.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Alternative service camps for conscientious objectors were set up in Banff during World War II, with camps at Lake Louise, Stoney Creek, and Healy Creek.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] These camps were largely populated by Mennonites from Saskatchewan.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Winter tourism in Banff began in February 1917, with the first Banff Winter Carnival.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] It was marketed to a regional middle class audience, and became the centerpiece of local boosters aiming to attract visitors, which were a low priority for the Canadian Pacific Railway (CPR).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The carnival featured a large ice palace, which in 1917 was built by World War I internees.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Carnival events included cross-country skiing, ski jumping, curling, snowshoe, and skijoring.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the 1930s, the first downhill ski resort, Sunshine Village, was developed by the Brewsters.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Mount Norquay ski area was also developed during the 1930s, with the first chair lift installed there in 1948.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since 1968, when the Banff Springs Hotel was winterized, Banff has been a year-round destination.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the 1950s, the Trans-Canada Highway was constructed, providing another transportation corridor through the Bow Valley, making the park more accessible.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Canada launched several bids to host the Winter Olympics in Banff, with the first bid for the 1964 Winter Olympics, which were eventually awarded to Innsbruck, Austria.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Canada narrowly lost a second bid, for the 1968 Winter Olympics, which were awarded to Grenoble, France.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Once again, Banff launched a bid to host the 1972 Winter Olympics, with plans to hold the Olympics at Lake Louise.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The 1972 bid was controversial, as environmental lobby groups strongly opposed the bid, which had sponsorship from Imperial Oil.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Bowing to pressure, Jean Chrétien, then the Minister of Environment, the government department responsible for Parks Canada, withdrew support for the bid, which was eventually lost to Sapporo, Japan.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] When nearby Calgary hosted the 1988 Winter Olympics, the cross-country ski events were held at the Canmore Nordic Centre Provincial Park at Canmore, Alberta, located just outside the eastern gates of Banff National Park on the Trans-Canada Highway.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since the original Rocky Mountains Park Act, subsequent acts and policies placed greater emphasis on conservation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With public sentiment tending towards environmentalism, Parks Canada issued major new policy in 1979, which emphasized conservation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The *National Parks Act* was amended in 1988, which made preserving ecological integrity the first priority in all park management decisions.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The act also required each park to produce a management plan, with greater public participation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With this designation came added obligations for conservation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] During the 1980s, Parks Canada moved to privatize many park services such as golf courses, and added user fees for use of other facilities and services to help deal with budget cuts.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1990, the town of Banff was incorporated, giving local residents more say regarding any proposed developments.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the 1990s, development plans for the park, including expansion at Sunshine Village, were under fire with lawsuits filed by Canadian Parks and Wilderness Society (CPAWS).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the mid-1990s, the Banff–Bow Valley Study was initiated to find ways to better address environmental concerns, and issues relating to development in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is in the Rocky Mountains on Alberta's western border with British Columbia in the Alberta Mountain forests ecoregion.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] By road, the town of Banff is 128 kilometres (80 mi) west of Calgary and 401 km (249 mi) southwest of Edmonton.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Jasper National Park borders Banff National Park to the north, while Yoho National Park is to the west and Kootenay National Park is to the south.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Kananaskis Country, which includes Bow Valley Wildland Provincial Park, Spray Valley Provincial Park, and Peter Lougheed Provincial Park, is located to the south and east of Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Trans-Canada Highway passes through Banff National Park, from the eastern boundary near Canmore, through the towns of Banff and Lake Louise, and into Yoho National Park in British Columbia.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Banff townsite is the main commercial centre in the national park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The village of Lake Louise is at the junction of the Trans-Canada Highway and the Icefields Parkway, which extends north to the Jasper townsite.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff, established in 1885, is the main commercial centre in Banff National Park, as well as a centre for cultural activities.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff is home to several cultural institutions, including the Banff Centre, the Whyte Museum, the Buffalo Nations Luxton Museum, Cave and Basin National Historic Site, and several art galleries.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Throughout its history, Banff has hosted many annual events, including Banff Indian Days which began in 1889, and the Banff Winter Carnival.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since 1976, The Banff Centre has organized the Banff Mountain Film Festival.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1990, Banff incorporated as a town of Alberta, though still subject to the *National Parks Act* and federal authority in regards to planning and development.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In its 2014 census, the town of Banff had a permanent population of 8,421 as well as 965 non-permanent residents for a total population of 9,386.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Bow River flows through the town of Banff, with the Bow Falls on the outskirts of town.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Lake Louise, a hamlet 54 km (34 mi) northwest of the town of Banff, is home to the landmark Chateau Lake Louise at the edge of Lake Louise.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Located 15 km (9.3 mi) from Lake Louise, Moraine Lake provides a scenic vista of the Valley of the Ten Peaks.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] This scene is on the back of the Canadian $20 bill in the 1969–1979 ("Scenes of Canada") series.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Lake Louise Mountain Resort is also near the village.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Lake Louise is one of the most visited lakes in the world and is framed to the southwest by the Mount Victoria Glacier.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Icefields Parkway is a 230-kilometre-long (140 mi) road connecting Lake Louise to Jasper, Alberta.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Parkway originates at Lake Louise, and extends north up the Bow Valley, past Hector Lake, which is the largest natural lake in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Other scenic lakes near the parkway include Bow Lake, and Peyto Lakes, both north of Hector Lake.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Parkway then crosses Bow Summit (2,088 m (6,850 ft)), and follows the Mistaya River to Saskatchewan Crossing, where it converges with the Howse and North Saskatchewan River.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Bow Summit is the highest elevation crossed by a public road in Canada.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The North Saskatchewan River flows east from Saskatchewan Crossing, out of Banff, into what is known as David Thompson Country, and onto Edmonton.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The David Thompson Highway follows the North Saskatchewan River, past the man-made Abraham Lake, and through David Thompson Country.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] North of Saskatchewan Crossing, the Icefields Parkway follows the North Saskatchewan River up to the Columbia Icefield.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Parkway crosses into Jasper National Park at Sunwapta Pass at 2,035 metres (6,677 ft) in elevation, and continues on from there to the Jasper townsite.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Canadian Rockies consist of several northwest–southeast trending ranges.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Two main mountain ranges are within the park, each consisting of numerous subranges.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The western border of the park follows the crest of the Main Ranges (also known as the *Park Ranges*), which is also the continental divide.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Main Ranges in Banff National Park include from north to south, the Waputik, Bow and Blue Ranges.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The high peaks west of Lake Louise are part of the Bow Range.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The eastern border of the park includes all of the Front Ranges consisting of from north to south, the Palliser, Sawback and Sundance Ranges.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Banff townsite is in the Front Ranges.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Just outside the park to the east lie the foothills that extend from Canmore at the eastern entrance of the park eastward into the Great Plains.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Well west of the park, the Western Ranges of the Rockies pass through Yoho and Kootenay National Parks.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Though the tallest peak entirely within the park is Mount Forbes at 3,612 metres (11,850 ft), Mount Assiniboine on the Banff-Mount Assiniboine Provincial Park border is slightly higher at 3,618 m (11,870 ft).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Canadian Rockies are composed of sedimentary rock, including shale, sandstone, dolomite and limestone.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The vast majority of geologic formations in Banff range in age from Precambrian to the Jurassic periods (600–145 m.y.a.).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] However, rocks as young as the lower Cretaceous (145–66 m.y.a.) can be found near the east entrance and on Cascade Mountain above the Banff townsite.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] These sedimentary rocks formed at the bottom of shallow seas between 600 and 175 m.y.a. and were pushed east during the Laramide orogeny.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Mountain building in Banff National Park ended approximately 55 m.y.a.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Canadian Rockies may have risen up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) approximately 70 m.y.a.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Once mountain formation ceased, erosion carved the mountains into their present rugged shape.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The erosion was first due to water, then was greatly accelerated by the Quaternary glaciation 2.5 million years ago.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Glacial landforms dominate Banff's geomorphology, with examples of all classic glacial forms, including cirques, arêtes, hanging valleys, moraines, and U-shaped valleys.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The pre-existing structure left over from mountain-building strongly guided glacial erosion: mountains in Banff include complex, irregular, anticlinal, synclinal, castellate, dogtooth, and sawback mountains.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Many of the mountain ranges trend northwest to southeast, with sedimentary layering dipping down to the west at 40–60 degrees.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] This leads to dip slope landforms, with generally steeper east and north faces, and trellis drainage, where rivers and old glacial valleys followed the weaker layers in the rocks as they were relatively easily weathered and eroded.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Classic examples are found at the Banff townsite proper: Mount Rundle is a classic dip slope mountain.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Just to the north of the Banff townsite, Castle Mountain is composed of numerous Cambrian age rock formations.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The uppermost section of the peak consists of relatively harder dolomite from the Eldon Formation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Below that lies the less dense shales of the Stephen Formation and the lowest exposed cliffs are limestones of the Cathedral Formation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Dogtooth mountains, such as Mount Louis, exhibit sharp, jagged slopes.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Sawback Range, which consists of nearly vertical dipping sedimentary layers, has been eroded by cross gullies.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The erosion of these almost vertical layers of rock strata in the Sawback Range has resulted in formations that appear like the teeth on a saw blade.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Erosion and deposition of higher elevation rock layers has resulted in scree deposits at the lowest elevations of many of the mountains.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park has numerous large glaciers and icefields, 100 of which can be observed from the Icefields Parkway.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Small cirque glaciers are fairly common in the Main Ranges, in depressions on the side of many mountains.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] As with the majority of mountain glaciers around the world, the glaciers in Banff are retreating.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] While Peyto Glacier is one of the longest continuously studied glaciers in the world, with research extending back to the 1970s, most of the glaciers of the Canadian Rockies have only been scientifically evaluated since the late 1990s.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Glaciologists are now researching the glaciers in the park more thoroughly, and have been analyzing the impact that reduced glacier ice may have on water supplies to streams and rivers.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Estimates are that 150 glaciers disappeared in the Canadian Rockies (areas both inside and outside Banff National Park) between 1920 and 1985.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Another 150 glaciers disappeared between 1985 and 2005, indicating that the retreat and disappearance of glaciers is accelerating.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In Banff National Park alone, in 1985 there were 365 glaciers but by 2005, 29 glaciers had disappeared.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The total glaciated area dropped from 625 to 500 square kilometres (241 to 193 sq mi) in that time period.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The largest glaciated areas include the Waputik and Wapta Icefields, which both lie on the Banff-Yoho National Park border.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Outlets of the Wapta Icefield on the Banff side of the continental divide include Peyto, Bow, and Vulture Glaciers.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Bow Glacier retreated an estimated 1,100 m (3,600 ft) between the years 1850 and 1953, and since that period, there has been further retreat which has left a newly formed lake at the terminal moraine.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Peyto Glacier has lost 70 percent of its volume since record keeping began and retreated approximately 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) between 1999 and 2021.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Peyto Glacier is at risk of losing 80-90% of its current mass by 2100.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Columbia Icefield, at the northern end of Banff, straddles the Banff and Jasper National Park border and extends into British Columbia.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Snow Dome, in the Columbia Icefield is a hydrological apex of North America, with water flowing via outlet glaciers to the Atlantic, Pacific and Arctic Oceans.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Saskatchewan Glacier, which is approximately 13 km (8 mi) in length and 30 km2 (12 sq mi) in area, is the major outlet of the Columbia Icefield that flows into Banff National Park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Between the years 1893 and 1953, Saskatchewan Glacier had retreated a distance of 1,364 m (4,475 ft), with the rate of retreat between 1948 and 1953 averaging 55 m (180 ft) per year.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Overall, the glaciers of the Canadian Rockies lost 25 percent of their mass during the 20th century.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Under the Köppen climate classification, the park has a subarctic climate (*Dfc*) with cold, snowy winters, and mild summers.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The climate is influenced by altitude with lower temperatures generally found at higher elevations.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Located on the eastern side of the Continental Divide, Banff National Park receives 454.0 mm (17.87 in) of precipitation annually.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] This is considerably less than in Yoho National Park on the western side of the divide in British Columbia, where 884.2 mm (34.81 in) (1971-1990 normals) is received at Wapta Lake and approximately 1,282 mm (50.5 in) at Boulder Creek annually.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Being influenced by altitude, snowfall is also greater at higher elevations.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] As such, 183.8 cm (72.4 in) (1991–2020 normals) of snow falls on average each year in the Banff townsite, while 279.1 cm (109.9 in) (1981-2010 normals) falls in Lake Louise, which is at a higher altitude, 1,524 m (5,000 ft).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] During winter months, temperatures in Banff are moderated, compared to other areas of central and northern Alberta, due to Chinook winds and other influences from British Columbia.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The mean low temperature during January is −13.5 °C (7.7 °F), and the mean high temperature is −3.5 °C (25.7 °F) for the town of Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] However, temperatures can drop below −20 °C (−4 °F) with wind chill values dropping below −30 for 3.5 days in an average year.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Weather conditions during summer months are warm, with high temperatures during July averaging 22.5 °C (72.5 °F), and daily low temperatures averaging 6.8 °C (44.2 °F), leading to a large diurnal range owing to the relative dryness of the air.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park spans three ecoregions, including montane, subalpine, and alpine.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The subalpine ecoregion, which consists mainly of dense forest, comprises 53 percent of Banff's area.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] 27 percent of the park is located above the tree line, in the alpine ecoregion.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The tree line in Banff lies approximately at 2,300 m (7,500 ft), with open meadows at alpine regions and some areas covered by glaciers.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A small portion (3 percent) of the park, at lower elevations, is in the montane ecoregion.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Lodgepole pine forests dominate the montane region of Banff, with Engelmann spruce, willow, aspen, occasional Douglas-fir and a few Douglas maple interspersed.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Engelmann spruce are more common in the subalpine regions of Banff, with some areas of lodgepole pine, and subalpine fir.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The montane areas in the Bow Valley, which tend to be the preferred habitat for wildlife, have been subjected to significant human development over the years.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The park has 56 recorded mammal species.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Grizzly bears and black bears inhabit the forested regions.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Cougar, lynx, wolverine, red fox, weasel, river otter, coyote, and grey wolf are the primary predatory mammals.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Elk, mule deer, and white-tailed deer are common in the valleys of the park, including around (and sometimes in) the Banff townsite, while moose tend to be more elusive, sticking primarily to wetland areas and near streams.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the alpine regions, mountain goat, bighorn sheep, marmot and pika are widespread.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Other mammals such as beaver, porcupine, squirrel, chipmunk, snowshoe hare, and Columbian ground squirrel are the more commonly observed smaller mammals.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Caribou were the rarest large mammals in the park, but an avalanche in 2009 may have killed the last five remaining within park boundaries.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The American bison was extirpated in Banff, but was brought back to the park in 2017, and one free-roaming herd lives within the protected area.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Due to the harsh winters, the park has few reptile and amphibian species with only one species of toad, three species of frog, one salamander species and two species of snakes that have been identified.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] At least 280 species of birds can be found in Banff including bald and golden eagles, red-tailed hawk, osprey, and merlin, all of which are predatory species.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Additionally, commonly seen species such as the Canada jay, American three-toed woodpecker, mountain bluebird, Clark's nutcracker, mountain chickadee and pipit are frequently found in the lower elevations.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The white-tailed ptarmigan is a ground bird that is often seen in the alpine zones.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Rivers and lakes are frequented by over a hundred different species including loon, heron and mallard which spend their summers in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Endangered species in Banff include the Banff Springs snail (*Physella johnsoni*) that is found in the hot springs of Banff, and the woodland caribou.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Mountain pine beetles have caused a number of large-scale infestations in Banff National Park, feeding on the phloem of mature lodgepole pines.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Alberta's first known outbreak occurred in 1940, infecting 43 km2 (17 sq mi) of forest in Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A second major outbreak occurred in the late 1970s and early 1980s in Banff and the surrounding Rocky Mountains region.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is the most visited Alberta tourist destination and one of the most visited national parks in North America, with more than three million tourists annually.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Tourism in Banff contributes an estimated CA$6 billion annually to the economy.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A park pass is required for stopping in the park, and permit checks are common during the summer months, especially at Lake Louise and the start of the Icefields Parkway.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A permit is not required if travelling straight through the park without stopping.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Approximately 5 million people pass through Banff annually on the Trans-Canada Highway without stopping.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 2009, Banff Lake Louise Tourism hoped the appearance of the "Crasher Squirrel" internet meme would stimulate interest in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is managed by Parks Canada, under the *National Parks Act* which was passed in 1930.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Over time, park management policies have increasingly emphasized environmental protection over development.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1964, a policy statement was issued that reiterated ideals of conservation laid out in the 1930 act.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With the controversial bid for the 1972 Winter Olympics, environmental groups became more influential, leading Parks Canada to withdraw its support for the bid.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The 1979 Beaver Book was a major new policy, which emphasized conservation.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1988, the *National Parks Act* was amended, making the maintenance of ecological integrity the top priority.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The amendment also paved the way for non-governmental organizations to challenge Parks Canada in court, for breaches in adhering to the act.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1994, Parks Canada established revised "Guiding Principles and Operating Policies", which included a mandate for the Banff–Bow Valley Study to draft management recommendations.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] As with other national parks, Banff is required to have a Park Management Plan.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] On a provincial level, the park area and the included communities (other than the town of Banff which is an incorporated municipality) are administered by Alberta Municipal Affairs as Improvement District No.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The park was originally considered as a recreational area for visitors offering multiple leisure activities – the original wildlife policy viewed wildlife in Banff only as game or pests up until the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] As ecological awareness increased, management procedures expanded with the inclusion of public participation in many management decisions.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Simultaneously, the increase in human construction (such as new highways) on the natural landscape increased the frequency of human–animal conflicts.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1988 wildlife began to be considered an integral part of the ecosystem.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The park now has a number of wildlife management strategies that aim to conserve certain species.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Parks Canada uses an ecosystem based management approach that aims to preserve the ecology of the park while still providing for visitors.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Management decisions are based on modern scientific ecological information as well as traditional knowledge.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Elk are a very important species in Banff National Park, partly because they represent a source of food for declining wolves.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] However they also have harsh impacts on the environment.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Large elk populations cause vegetation degradation, human–animal conflicts and destabilization of biological interactions.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1999, the implementation of the Banff National Park Elk Management Strategy by Parks Canada and the Elk Advisory Committee aimed to monitor and control the population to decrease conflicts and aid ecological process recovery.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Elk handling facilities are areas of pens with loading and unloading ramps where water and food are provided to the elk.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] They were created to help reduce herd numbers by increasing wariness and encouraging migratory behaviour, deterring the elk from the town of Banff.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] These measures allowed more predator–prey interactions thanks to the creation of corridors.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] They also increased elk migration, restored the willow and aspen communities and highlighted the primary role of wolves in elk population management.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The state of grizzly bear populations in Banff is seen as a proxy for ecological integrity.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] To keep bears away from humans, an electric fence was put up around the summer gondola and parking lot at Lake Louise in 2001.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Bear-proof garbage cans, which do not allow bears to access their contents, help to deter them from human sites.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The fruit of buffaloberry bushes is eaten by bears, so the bushes have been removed in some areas where the risk of a bear–human encounter is high.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Aversive conditioning deters bears by modifying their behaviour.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Deterrents such as noise makers and rubber bullets are used each time the bear performs an undesirable action.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Advice is also given to people to avoid an eventual habituation of bears to human presence.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] If this conditioning is continual the bear will be less likely to continue the undesirable behaviour (crossing into campsites and roads etc.).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Southern mountain caribou management previously aimed to identify what was threatening caribou populations and find solutions to mitigate the threats, but the last caribou in the park was found dead in an avalanche in 2009.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] There was concern over why more had not been done to save the caribou population.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The primary reason for their decline is thought to have been habitat loss and altered predator–prey dynamics.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Park management began monitoring the last five caribou in the park in 2002 and taking actions such as reducing impacts of humans, conducting studies of the population, and investigating the possibility of translocating caribou to increase the Banff population.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In the mid-1980s gray wolves recolonized the Bow Valley in Banff National Park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] They had been absent for 30 years due to systematic predator control hunting which began in 1850.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Wolves filtered back to Banff and recolonized one zone of the Bow Valley in 1985 and another in 1991.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A high level of human use surrounding a third zone at Banff townsite has deterred the wolves from that area.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The wolves are important in controlling elk populations and improve the balance of the ecosystem.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A routine park study to monitor the wolves in Banff has now grown into the Southern Rockies Canine Project – the largest wolf research project in North America.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The estimated wolf population in Banff National Park and the surrounding areas is now 60–70 animals.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Plains bison were reintroduced to Banff in 2017.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The park has an extensive system of grasslands in backcountry valleys that are perfect for the bison.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] 16 bison were translocated from Elk Island National Park and initially placed under observation for a year in an enclosed pasture within a 1,200 square kilometres (460 sq mi) reintroduction site near Panther River Valley.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] After 18 months of acclimation, the herd was released into the reintroduction site and as of August 2021, the herd had grown to 66.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Wildlife crossings have been successful in Banff National Park at reducing the number of animals killed on the roads.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] There is also 82 kilometres (51 mi) of fencing at the edge of the highway in the park to prevent animals from getting onto the roads.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since it was put up, this has reduced collisions between wildlife and vehicles by over 80 per cent.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Train tracks still pose challenges to conservationists.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Many bears have been killed by trains, often because they are attracted to grain spills along the tracks.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Transportation corridors provide openings for plants which are also utilized by bears.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A partnership between Parks Canada and Canadian Pacific Railway allowed the creation of the first Railway-Bear Conflict Mitigation Symposium in 2010.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Initiatives included building wooden pegboards to fence off the sides of tracks and chemically treating grains to deter the bears.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] After a complete review of the research projects, the development of some of them has been authorized, including grain alteration and the use of cameras to study the behavioural response of bears to trains.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 2011, Parks Canada began to study the effectiveness of electro-mats, large mats that give a small electric shock to animals that step on them, as a potential deterrent around train tracks.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] A trial instalment of the mats was placed in Banff to test their effectiveness in deterring animals like bears from gaining access to the fenced train tracks inside the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] General prohibitions implemented to ensure wildlife respect include the prohibition of feeding, touching, or holding animals in captivity, and the disturbance or destruction of bird nests.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since the 19th century, humans have impacted Banff's environment through introduction of non-native species, controls on other species, and development in the Bow Valley, among other human activities.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Bison once lived in the valleys of Banff and were hunted by indigenous people, but the last bison were killed off in 1850s.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 2017 a small herd of sixteen plains bison were reintroduced into an eastern section of the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Elk are not indigenous to Banff, and were introduced in 1917 with 57 elk brought in from Yellowstone National Park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The introduction of elk to Banff, combined with controls on coyote and wolves by Parks Canada beginning in the 1930s, has caused imbalance of the ecosystem.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Other species that have been displaced from the Bow Valley include grizzly bears, cougars, lynx, wolverine, otter, and moose.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Beginning in 1985, gray wolves were recolonizing areas in the Bow Valley.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] However, the wolf population has struggled, with 32 wolf deaths along the Trans-Canada Highway between 1987 and 2000, leaving only 31 wolves in the area.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The population of bull trout and other native species of fish in Banff's lakes has also dwindled, with the introduction of non-native species including brook trout, and rainbow trout.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Lake trout, westslope cutthroat trout, and chiselmouth are rare native species, while chinook salmon, white sturgeon, Pacific lamprey, and Banff longnose dace are likely extirpated locally.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Banff longnose dace, once only found in Banff, is now an extinct species.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Trans-Canada Highway, passing through Banff, has been problematic, posing hazards for wildlife due to vehicle traffic and as an impediment to wildlife migration.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Grizzly bears are among the species impacted by the highway, which together with other developments in Banff, has caused fragmentation of the landscape.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Grizzly bears prefer the montane habitat, which has been most impacted by development.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Wildlife crossings, including a series of underpasses, and six wildlife overpasses, have been constructed at a number of points along the Trans-Canada Highway to help alleviate this problem.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Parks Canada management practices, notably fire suppression, since Banff National Park was established have impacted the park's ecosystem.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Since 1983, Parks Canada has adopted a strategy that employed prescribed burns, which helps to mimic effects of natural fires.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Banff National Park is bisected by two highways that cross the Alberta/British Columbia border while another provides a third access within Alberta.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The Trans-Canada Highway (Highway 1) bisects the park in an east–west direction, connecting it to Vancouver to the west and Calgary to the east.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Highway 93 bisects the park in a north–south direction, connecting it to Cranbrook to the south and Jasper to the north.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The portion of Highway 93 north of Lake Louise is known as the Icefields Parkway whereas the portion southwest of Castle Junction is known as the Banff-Windermere Parkway.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Highway 11 (the David Thompson Highway) connects the Icefields Parkway at Saskatchewan River Crossing to Rocky Mountain House to the northeast.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Within the park, Highway 1A, also known as the Bow Valley Parkway, loosely parallels Highway 1 between Banff and Lake Louise.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The closest airport with long-haul flights is Calgary International Airport (YYC).
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] There is a registered aerodrome (Banff Aerodrome, (IATA: **YBA**, ICAO: **CYBA**)) operated by Parks Canada located in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The aerodrome requires prior permission for use.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Other transportation facilities within Banff National Park include a Canadian Pacific rail line that generally parallels Highway 1, and Banff Park Compound Heliport.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1978, expansion of Sunshine Village ski resort was approved, with added parking, hotel expansion, and development of Goat's Eye Mountain.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Implementation of this development proposal was delayed through the 1980s, while environmental assessments were conducted.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1989, Sunshine Village withdrew its development proposal, in light of government reservations, and submitted a revised proposal in 1992.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] This plan was approved by the government, pending environmental review.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Subsequently, the Canadian Parks and Wilderness Society (CPAWS) filed a court injunction, which halted the development.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] CPAWS also put pressure on UNESCO to revoke Banff's World Heritage Site status, over concerns that developments were harming the park's ecological health.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] While the *National Parks Act* and the 1988 amendment emphasize ecological integrity, in practice Banff has suffered from inconsistent application of the policies.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In 1994, the Banff–Bow Valley Study was mandated by Sheila Copps, the minister responsible for Parks Canada, to provide recommendations on how to better manage human use and development, and maintain ecological integrity.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] While the two-year Banff–Bow Valley Study was underway, development projects were halted, including the expansion of Sunshine Village, and the twinning of the Trans-Canada Highway between Castle Junction and Sunshine.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The panel issued over 500 recommendations, including limiting the growth of the Banff townsite, capping the town's population at 10,000, placing quotas for popular hiking trails, and curtailing development in the park.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Another recommendation was to fence off the townsite to reduce confrontations between people and elk.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] The proposed fencing was also intended to reduce access to this refuge for elk from predators, such as wolves that tended to avoid the townsite.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Upon release of the report, Copps immediately moved to accept the proposal to cap the town population.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] She also ordered a small airstrip to be removed, along with a buffalo paddock, and cadet camp, that inhibited wildlife movement.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] In response to concerns and recommendations raised by the Banff–Bow Valley Study, a number of development plans were curtailed in the 1990s.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Plans to add nine holes at the Banff Springs Golf Resort were withdrawn in 1996.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] With the cap on growth in the town of Banff, Canmore, located just outside the Banff boundary, has been growing rapidly to serve increasing demands of tourists.
[src:banff-national-park/banff-national-park] Major development proposals for Canmore have included the Three Sisters Golf Resorts, proposed in 1992, which has been the subject of contentious debate, with environmental groups arguing that the development would fragment important wildlife corridors in the Bow Valley.
